reviewText: YES! Can't wait!

This review is mostly for season pass purchasers.  Please read in its entirety before rating it helpful or not.
  The Walking Dead is an amazing series so far that has kept me coming back each year.  As the season progresses I will promptly give it the 5 (really like 4.5 if I could) stars the series has earned

  The season pass purchases seems to have changed, I assume so people don't get a discount on one episode and then stop purchasing.  I was hesitant to purchase the season pass after reading the 1 star review but did anyway.  I was mostly curious if the season pass discount would apply since I didn't notice any mention of how much it was.  Here is how the bill broke down.

$41.99 (HD)
Item Subtotal: $41.99
Promotions:  -$6.00
Tax Collected: $0.00
Grand Total: $35.99

So it appears the $6 is the discount for the season pass purchase and the $41.99 is the cost for the season if episodes are purchased individually.

 I hope this helps someone out there; I can't wait for the premier!

My high school age boys and I have been hooked since day one. A great series about the exponential decay of societal norms once routine lifestyles are shattered by disaster. We learn a lot about humanity, ethical choices in light of physical needs, and so much more. These issues come to life during any number of real micro-disasters occurring around the world from hurricane and floods to war zones, etc.

This is an absolutely amazing show in how it handles the post apocalyptic behaviour of an ever changing group of people.  It deviated from the comic books and tells it's own store, and it is a lot of fun to watch.  Characters grow and change, people die, and others are forced to move on.

This season is moving in the right direction with a lot of major changes and new situations.  The group they are stuck with now is going to make this a fantastic season because things are going so badly.  It is very true to life because people don't always make the right choices and things don't always just work out in that fairy-tale way a lot of shows have.

Give it a try. Start at the beginning or play catch up. It is totally worth it.
Anxiously awaiting Oct. 12th. Best show ever.

What do you say about a show that while professing to be about zombies is really one of the best dramas to hit the airwaves in years.  We follow the adventures of our group while being scared to death not of zombies as much as the fact that the producers of this show have already proven on multiple occasions that pretty much nobody is safe and can be killed off (we assume that Rick is a constant but who knows)

This season is even more stressful than most since the last season ended on what looks to be a hopeless situation and we don't know if we are dealing with cannibals or what.  hang on for the ride because if there is one thing I have learned by watching every episode and that is you really cannot predict what this show is going to do (as evidenced by one particular gut wrenching episode from last season I never saw coming)

Entertainment at its finest and the zombies when you get down to it are not much more than background clutter.

UPDATE:  I was sure they were gonna drag the Teminus thing throughout the first few episodes and to say I am VERY happy they did not would be an understatement, Rick was awesome!

Minor Spoiler:  What about the Samurai sword??? I love that sword!  (and it finally comes home:)  )

Update:  Talk about your stupid villains, once again, they had no idea who they were screwing with and it showed.  I did love Bob playing them for fools with their Bob-B-Q

Look... I am so sick of Walking Dead "fans" that moan & complain about every single episode. This show is as close to perfection as you will find out there... and if there is any doubt about that, then exhibit A is Season 6.

The show started great and has improved year after year. For me--an actual fan and not a "fan"--Season 6 is my favorite. The writing is tight and the performances are award worthy... and, just a quick tangent--speaking of awards: why is a show with incest, dragons and frozen zombies heavily nominated for Emmies and a far more realistic show with regular zombies snubbed year after year? Don't get me wrong--I love Game of Thrones--but it just seems so wrong. Is it cause one show is based on a literary book and the other is based on a comic book? If so, I have to say, at least Robert Kirkman actually continues to write and finish his projects in a timely fashion... ya' hear me over there, Mr. R.R. Martin?

Anyhow... Season 6 is, in my honest opinion, absolute perfection! And if you are, in fact, one of THOSE "fans" and all you do is complain... may I suggest you go watch a show you actually enjoy, like Big Bang Theory or some other inane swill, and let the actual fans of TWD appreciate the show we so dearly love. Thanks! Buh-bye and hope this helps.

TWD, you are either all in or all out. I thought about taking a star off for lame or stilted dialogue, but held off. Sometimes dialogue starts going awry and motivations for characters seem goofy. BUT TWD is bigger than all that, and we move on 'til it gets better, right? I'm sure life would be much darker than it is portrayed here, but I like dark. The best episodes are the ones where the characters are searching an abandoned town, house, or building, because that is what life would be like almost all the time. A caveman like existence of hunting and gathering would be life in the after world. I enjoy the conflicts with the baddies that are still alive, but would everyone be bad? There are more creepy people than good people. Now I'm firmly convinced we have too many bad people in today's world, but not like the TWD world where 90% are bad. I like a little bit of realism in my dystopian zombie dramas. Like Z-Nation, I gave up on that one as too goofy. Season 6 is good, but I don't know yet what I'm going to say about Season 7 that just seemed to drag on with the heroes and 'professional survivalists' getting their butts handed to them daily. MOVE OUTTA TOWN, OR GO TO COLORADO!! Season 6 is a well worth the view effort.

Rick Grimes and his fellow survivors have found a new home in the town of Alexandria. The original inhabitants were organised but lacking in steel, not having seen off the challenges experienced by Rick and his companions. Having helped defend the town from threats within and without, Rick finds himself the de facto new leader of the community and has to take action against an imminent new danger: a vast horde of walkers located in a nearby quarry who are on the verge of breaking out and destroying the town. Beyond that, there are other threats lurking outside the walls, a band of raiders called the Wolves...and another, more mysterious group called the Saviors.

The Walking Dead is probably the most frustrating show on television (although it's also traded that title a few times with Game of Thrones in its most recent two seasons). It's beautifully shot, fantastically scored and has an outstanding cast of excellent actors. The writing and characterisation, however, is highly variable and the show's tone can go all over the place, from slightly cartoonish ultraviolence to gritty realism to funny character interactions and back again, often in a very clunky fashion. By far the show's biggest problem, however, has been pacing and structure. The series has had sixteen episodes per season since its third year, which is very generous by modern American cable standards, but it has struggled, sometimes excruciatingly, with filling that time with consistently gripping drama. From its third through fifth seasons, The Walking Dead has made wheel-spinning into an almost admirable art form.

For its sixth year, the show takes a different tack and one that is quite successful in solving this problem. The first half of the season revolves around two entwined events: Rick and his friends driving off a walker horde at the same time some opportunistic scavengers called the Wolves attack Alexandria. This results in a complex, two-front battle which becomes even more challenging when part of the horde splits off and crashes the party in town. This results in The Walking Dead's most action-packed storyline to date, with eight episodes of building tension, drama and all-out warfare. The series has often been criticised for sometimes forgetting there's even zombies around (although that was kind of Robert Kirkman's point, the zombies are merely the mechanism by which civilisation falls whilst he is far more interested in the social dynamics of reconstruction) but that complaint is certainly dismissed this season. The first few episodes of the show have our characters going to war, engaging the walkers in a full-scale, all-out offensive to save their new home.

It's all splendid stuff. The characters get their moments in the sun, Carol and Tara get new romantic partners, someone gives Daryl a rocket launcher and we're reunited with (slightly inexplicably) fan-favourite bit-player Morgan, who finally joins the cast full-time and gives us the possibly the show's most bizarre stand-alone episode in which he learns aikido from a random dude in the woods and his goat. This episode is gloriously insane, makes very little sense and seems to think it's very profound, which makes it awesomely enjoyable (if not quite for the reasons the writers intended). The first half of the season is The Walking Dead at its very strongest and most gripping, even if the decision to "kill" Glen and hide his fate for three episodes remains utterly moronic.

The second half starts going a bit wonky almost immediately. The end of the battle for Alexandria sees several characters introduced at the end of Season 5 brutally murdered apparently just to keep the cast costs down, which is less tragic than just annoying. Things pick up with a fantastic Daryl/Rick road trip episode in which they meet a charismatic new character called Jesus and then learn about the existence of a network of other settlements. At this point the show's allusions to the Fallout video game series (which have always been present, if not in the actual setting, then in the general post-apocalyptic tone) pick up as Rick moves from being on the defensive to gaining a view of a new civilisation arising from the survivors, that maybe they do all have a future. Having snatched away the possibility of a cure for the Turn in Season 5, The Walking Dead makes up for it by giving us a sliver of hope that maybe things will turn out okay.

There is, of course, a problem: the newly-contacted settlements are being extorted for food and ammo by a group called the Saviors. The show very nearly does something great here by having Rick and co immediately agree to attack them without actually talking to them first, which is a startlingly ruthless (and strategically unsound) move, and thus instigate hostilities. Unfortunately the series provides a get-out clause by revealing that they're the same group that attacked them earlier in the season (and had to be sorted out by Daryl and his rocket launcher), immediately giving Team Rick the moral high ground. This only increases when we get to meet the Saviours and discover just what a bunch of bad 'uns they are. Even so, the show makes some very interesting dramatic choices, such as having our first major interaction with the group come through a group of ruthless women who have sworn in with them, resulting in an unexpectedly feminist episode where they take Carol and Maggie prisoner and we're waiting for Rick to burst in and save them, but this turns out to be unnecessary because Carol and Maggie know how to take care of business by themselves.

So if the second half of the season falters compared to the first half, at least it's making interesting and original storytelling decisions, deploying its large cast of characters in dramatically compelling ways and keeping things ticking over nicely. And then it really all goes horribly wrong in the finale.

The Season 6 finale of The Walking Dead has been justly reviled by very large numbers of both critics and fans. One of the most interesting things about the Saviors before this point is that they're nasty and ruthless, but arguably not outright evil (their insistence on murdering one person as an example has to be countered with Rick's willingness to murder all of them without even knowing anything about them), and in fact seem to be what Team Rick were on their way to becoming given a few more months. The Saviors have some wins and losses, and seem to be a match for our heroes without totally overwhelming them (as, say, the Governor did initially). In the Season 6 finale the Saviors become psychic super-savants, capable of working out exactly what roads (ut of the utter maze of highways, back roads and side-trails sprawling outside Washington, DC our heroes are going to take and blocking them off expertly, building petrol-strewn barricades in minutes and knowing precisely where our characters will stop to get out of their truck to risk a cross-country run so they can set an elaborate trap. It's the most unconvincing, contrived bit of writing I've seen in years and is embarrassingly stupid. The silliness of this ending takes away from the introduction of Negan, the Saviors' much-foreshadowed leader, played with relish by the always-good Jeffrey Dean Morgan, and really reduces the impact of his ruthless execution of one of our heroes (not that you find out who that is until Season 7).

So the sixth season of The Walking Dead (****) is very nearly the best (and is certainly the best-structured and paced), but then makes a series of writing decisions throughout the season which are needlessly annoying, particularly its reliance on fake-out deaths. But as frustrating as it can be, The Walking Dead can also be, particularly in its quieter moments of just dwelling on the world after the fall, surprisingly atmospheric and thoughtful. The show's never-ending quest for consistency continues

The very first horror movie I ever saw was Romero's original Night of the Living Dead when I was 8... I had nightmares that night that I still remember every detail of now, 24 years later, and it's been my absolute favorite film of all time since then. So that film has kind of become the template that I measure all other undead, and horror films in general, up to. To me, NOTLD is the greatest horror film ever made... it created the ultimate terrifying concept... the dead coming back to life and devouring the living. This was not only a concept way ahead of its time in 1968, but the style of horror and atmosphere were unprecedented in those days. Most horror films were very tame, even in those days because people could tell "it was just a movie"... but NOTLD introduced a realism that people hadn't seen before. I know this isn't a review section for NOTLD but I'm going somewhere with this...

Today, the horror genre is OVERFLOODED with zombie films, to the point that the undead are no longer scary, but cute and lovable... which is why SO many zombie comedies are being rolled off the conveyor belt. The Walking Dead is probably the first non-Romero cinema dealing with the undead that gets the idea of the zombie right SINCE Romero's films. They should be dark, bleak, and horrifying stories, but most modern films portray zombies as "monsters" that scream and run rather than the reanimated corpses of the living... can you see the difference? A DEAD BODY CANNOT RUN BECAUSE IT'S BONES AND MUSCLES ARE TOO BRITTLE... that's why the more realistic films had them shambling. It all adds to the realism which adds to the fear we feel.

TWD does have one or two... "drawbacks" (for lack of a better word). For one, many of the stories start feeling a little too much like soap operas but when you compare them to 98% of the zombie movies that have come out since 2000, it's a WELCOME aspect since the storylines are focusing on.. well, STORY rather than gore overkill. Second, the thing that Romero hit the bullseye with was the fact that "They Are Us, and We Are Them"... TWD gets that to an extent, but in my opinion goes overboard on the gory makeup and the color scheme... let me explain... the living characters all have colors (clothing, skin, hair, everything), but the undead tend to just have a monochromatic color scheme... grey, white, brown, all cold colors that seem to blend together. So between the color and the makeup overkill, I feel like the show conveys more of an "Us vs Them" feeling rather than the more complicated "Us vs Them... but They ARE Us" inner struggle.

All in all, TWD is THE best zombie show or movie or book or whatever since George A Romero's Day of the Dead in 1985. Yes the 80s were full of excellent horror of all kinds, but the 90s fell off completely with horror, and when it made a come back in the 2000s, with the exception of indie and non-mainstream horror, the movies focused mostly on gore and special effects instead of character and story.

After reading the other reviews, I hesitated to buy the Limited Edition at the original price. When it was on the Amazon Deals for $99.99, I took the plunge. Still slightly disappointed that even at that price, it was the most I had paid for one of these Limited Edition sets, yet didn't do anything special like the other seasons' limited editions. (Two had moving parts, one lit up, and season five at least had a sliding top to access the DVDs in the hidden compartment.) For this, I deducted one star.
As for the season itself, I give it 5 stars. Loved seeing some of the back-story episodes, like how Morgan learned his fighting skills and pacifism, as well as leading up to the season finale. And no, I was not upset at all at the cliff-hanger at the end of the season. I had read the graphic novels and enjoyed seeing the new characters come to life and new communities being introduced, as well as some iconic moments from the graphic novels.

Rick Grimes and several of his fellow survivors are imprisoned in Terminus, a society of cannibals. They seek to escape whilst several of their friends, such as Carol, attempt a rescue. At the same time Beth finds herself a reluctant guest of a hospital in Atlanta. Out in the woods, a frightened priest cowers in his church. But the survivors now have a promise of salvation, a cure for the Turn, which calls them to Washington, DC...if they can survive.

The Walking Dead reaches its fifth season, in which everything is awesome and our heroes are happy and smiling. Or maybe not. The season opens with our heroes prisoners in a cannibal stronghold before joining forces with a priest losing his faith and ending with them deliberately traumatising a peaceful community into accepting them as their new protectors. Along the way several major characters die for no immediately-discernible reason and the writers tease the audience with the possibility of some kind of actual over-arching storyline with a firm resolution in mind before snatching it away, leaving both characters and viewers with no hope and to wallow in misery.

Or to put it another way, welcome to another season of The Walking Dead, y'all.

George Romero - someone who knows a thing or two about zombies - once called The Walking Dead a "zombie soap". He's not wrong. That's not a criticism, because Robert Kirkman also called the story that of a "zombie movie that never ends". Week in, week out, month in, month out, on screen, in the comics and in the video games, people tune into the next instalment of this story which tries to make a strength out of the fact it has no end, no master plan and no planned resolution.

This sense of an ongoing narrative works in soap operas, however, because of the shifts in tone. Yes, characters get divorced, get into fights, occasionally die, but they also get married, fall in love and have moments of real happiness. The Walking Dead's biggest problem has always been its nihilistic streak, that the world is full of misery and pain after the Turn and that both the walkers and other people are dangerous and out to kill you at any given moment and every day is a remorseless, never-ending struggle to feed yourself and your family, to avoid injury and disease, and to find shelter and ammo. Other TV shows embrace the darker side of life, but lighten things with moments of genuine humanity (like The Wire, whose cast The Walking Dead continues to pilfer for new roles), occasional comedy (Breaking Bad) or hope (Game of Thrones). The Walking Dead does this only very, very occasionally, which makes it a harder show to watch. It's the ultimate example of "grimdark" on television, with the strengths and weaknesses of that movement.

Season 5, like the past two seasons, attempts to overcome one of its biggest problems - the inability to sustain a narrative over 16 episodes - by dividing the season into two halves. The first half sees our heroes at their lowest ebb in Terminus, but they also have the hope of a cure and an endgame in mind. This ultimately proves a blind alley which is deeply frustrating, but perhaps true to the show's basic premise. Finding a cure for the walkers would, ultimately, feel like a cheap way of ending the series, even if it did provide some kind of upbeat resolution.

The first half of the season is a mixed bag. Our heroes spend way too much time hanging around in a church and the enemies they face from Terminus are characterless ciphers. There's a very half-hearted attempt to inject pathos by suggesting these people were once as good as Team Rick, but turned evil after meeting some bad people. But they never really follow up on it in enough depth to justify the sheer depravities they resort to. This part of the season also makes an ill-considered choice to use fractured, non-linear storytelling, moving from place to place, reversing back in time to fill in back story and accelerating forward again. Non-linear storytelling is a great device when handled well, but The Walking Dead uses it instead in this instance as a way of annoyingly retconning storylines and engaging in cheap emotional manipulation (when Person A was about to die and you thought Persons B and C were miles away, but it turns out in a flashback that Persons B and C were miles away hours earlier, and are now ready to save Person A). It also allows them to pad out the story with filler episodes in which not much happens. The Walking Dead TV show has always been far superior at characterisation than the comic books, and sometimes its use of quieter episodes to expand on character is effective. In the first half of Season 5 it never really works, however.

Once the show returns from its mid-season break, it regains a sense of momentum. Our heroes arrive on the outskirts of Washington, DC (those expecting some great shots of an abandoned Mall won't get them: the show's relatively low budget is never quite as painfully obvious as this season) and find a new safe haven, Alexandria. This results in a much more engaging storyline in which our heroes are presented as the unsafe invaders in a peaceful and stable community, Rick's ruthless pragmatism presented as cynical selfishness and maybe even outright villainy by the existing community leaders. This idea of turning Team Rick into the bad guys has always been an ace in the show's hole and their employment of it is well-assured, accompanied by some excellent performances. However, the show presents even this storyline with the training wheels still on. The revelation of a new group of bad guys who employ tactics far worse than anything Team Rick have done; some of the people in Alexandria turning out to be cowards and murderers; and the Alexandrians genuinely not having a clue about the world outside mean that our sympathies remain firmly lodged with Team Rick throughout. When offered a chance to make a genuinely interesting point on morality, The Walking Dead shrugs and keeps walkin' instead.

Still, The Walking Dead's primary strengths remain intact: some excellent actors, fantastic prosthetics work and some outstanding moments of cinematography and framing of shots. On a moment to moment basis, the show is mostly watchable and there are some outstanding action scenes. Carol (Melissa McBride) remains the best performer on the show, with some brilliant scenes and the opportunity to channel her inner soccer mom in the concluding episodes. She also gets most of the best lines. Many of the other actors also do quality work. But the sense remains that the show needs more of a sense of an endgame and more of a direction to the story. A zombie soap is great fun, there's only so long that it can keep doing that and remain fresh.

This season was a little slow, but I really liked the character development. I was peeved by -- *SPOILER* -- Beth's sudden death, and was hoping for her character to become more involved with the group, although I initially didn't notice her character much. I was also bothered by how she didn't really mourn her father's death in season 4 and basically just irritated Daryl, but every person is different in how they grieve. I did not enjoy her episodes, but that's my own personal taste. I found the second half of the season a bit tenser and tighter than the first half and I enjoy seeing Rick become a bit unhinged.

This is my favorite season to date! I like how a lot of these storylines will continue into the following season, although I wasn't a big fan of the season finale. I understand that the writers didn't want to overwhelm the viewers with a brutal death nor did they want Negan's entrance to be overlooked by the death. But it felt a bit cheap. Plus, it is impossible to keep a secret like a character death unspoiled for 6 months.
  That being said, the best episode (as well as my favorite) aired in this season called "No Way Out", and it proves any naysayers wrong who think that the show lost it's direction after season 4. Some very brilliant episodes aired and lots of tension ensued, especially with the mark of Negan. Carol is, in my opinion, the most interesting and complex one in the group and has yet another development in her character that some people won't understand, yet is necessary in order to keep her from becoming too one-dimensional and like a caricature. I thought it made sense that she would eventually have a breakdown emotionally, as she is the one who has grown the most and struggled the most with comprehending her conscious in her actions.
  Great season and I look forward to season 7.

I do not so much mind zombie violence since, after all, these poor folks are already dead, and de-animating them can be seen as a mercy really.  But, since the time at the prison, the show has shifted away from human against zombie violence to human against human violence. I accept that any apocalyptic situation is likely to produce violent characters, so its not unreasonable story-making.  But, I find human violence disturbing and not entertaining to watch.  Also with this change, the zombies are being reduced to backdrops, mere bothersome gnats to be shooed out of the way as the characters hunt down the next human to kill.  Perhaps such changes are necessary to keep the show from being repetitive, and I know some efforts are made the follow the graphic novels.  So, no complaints, just not my cup of tea anymore.  To those continuing with the series, godspeed my friends.

It makes you feel like you are there with them, feeling what they are feeling and they are your family that you would lay down your life to protect. It is just amazing. I couldn't wait to get home to watch more episodes and get caught up to where we are now waiting for season 7. In which I am very nervous about because I don't want to see any of them killed but when it happens I know I will be yelling at the TV. I can't believe they are having one of them die. This is crazy. Season Six of the Walking Dead keeps up the pace and the tension throughout the season we've come to expect. It does end on a cliffhanger, but so what?It's a TV series not a movie, unless they never make a seventh season a cliff hanger doesn't matter. You're definitely left wanting to see what happens next. In the sixth season, the walking dead aren't such a problem, especially now that they have the walls of Alexandria.  But Rick has discovered a quarry full of hungry corpses who have been trapped in a bottleneck type scenario.  A truck keeping them trapped on one side is obviously going to fall soon, so he'll need to come up with a plan and convince the Alexandria residents who still don't really realise their life of hot showers and cookies is in jeopardy if they do nothing.  Also like any zombie scenario, the biggest threat for survival isn't from zombies but is from those who are alive.  Season six will have a number of run ins, with various threats.  At times you actually wonder if Rick and Alexandria's residents are actually much different to those who are a threat to them but this group is the way we are vicariously living this zombie outbreak world.

It's five stars for enjoyment although this season has a few zombies who aren't looking as believable as in previous seasons. Obviously less of the budget is being spent on the dead characters. Some look like someone's wearing a rubber mask at times.  There's also on two episodes some editing errors at the start of the episodes, where we see a scene, then we see the same frames repeated in either a shorter or longer with other footage repeat.  Perhaps this is only a problem for the region 4 DVD set but you'd think it should have been noticed.

Region 4's DVD set is across six DVDs.  Nothing but episodes on the first five discs, with the sixth full of special features such as the usual from previous seasons analysis of each episode which goes for over an hour. There's also the usual making of, and a say goodbye to each of the main characters who died.  A few deleted scenes. Quite a few other extras as well.

Delivered quickly! As far as WD season 6 goes, you cannot go wrong with this series. FWD flash forwards in the beginning of each episode make this season a bit confusing at times , and it slows up a bit in parts, but the cliffhanger at the end will have you counting down the days for another year until season 7 arrives for sale!  The latter seasons of this series have less gore and guts than the season 1 and 2, (but still have more gore than most!) and as the series evolves, our band of heroic and not so heroic survivors in this series faces much more danger from other bands of humans outside the walls of their settlement, --(most of them quite brutal),  than they do from the roaming herds of drooling , snarling , rotting, flesh-starved walkers that are always slowly stumbling around that can kill a human in hours with just a bite or a scratch. Central themes are having the courage and stomach to fight, and TRUST--just who do you trust? And whom do you NOT TRUST when you come across other survivors out on the road while doing supply runs? Also do you preemptively do a surprise attack on another band of humans when you have evidence that they may very likely attack you and raid and pillage your settlement,  if you do not do it first? Anyway, have thoroughly enjoyed this series since season one!
If you can get past the gore,  I very very highly recommend!

What I've enjoyed most about this series is the amazing cast, and the existential questions raised by the story line, not only about what kind of life is worth living, but what kind of person it's worth being when devastated by loss, surrounded by ugliness, and forced to kill or be killed. By the time we get to Season 6, however, the characters have already met way too many depraved murderers who are not zombies. They've wrung their hands and searched their souls. They've lost those closest to them. They've died to save others. They've beaten back hordes of rotting dead people who, despite being so mushy they are literally coming to pieces, still somehow have the strength to push through walls. Season 6 takes the cycle of zombie fighting and crazy-live person fighting too far. There are too many unbelievably close calls. They are too many truly stupid communities. How many roving bands of vicious ruthless maniacs can anyone reasonably expect to encounter during the same zombie apocalypse? How many zombie invasions can even the most resourceful group successfully withstand? How much hand-wringing would anyone bother to do over his or her lost humanity when the choice is survival or death? At what point would the characters simply stop caring? The show needs to be wrapped up before the characters themselves die of boredom, or it needs to go in an entirely new direction.

A copy of this title was provided for review purposes.

Some shows continue to get better with age. THE WALKING DEAD has become just one of those shows. It could end up stale, with storylines repeated and nothing new added to the mix. Instead it always keeps you guessing, always challenges your emotions and offers one of the best dramas on TV today. While never receiving the kudos it deserves or even being nominated for an outstanding drama Emmy, it is far and above most dramas on TV today.

And let me say that this is a shame. Far too many write this series off as nothing more than a horror story, a show thats all about flesh eating zombies and trying to survive. Those that think this are missing the bigger picture and my guess is theyve not watched more than 2 or 3 episodes. The reality is that while there is the whole zombie apocalypse story going on thats not what the focus of the series is. Its focus is on the people trapped in this situation, how they survive, how they relate to one another and the lives they try to form together in the midst of this situation.

At the end of season five the people of the town of Alexandria were forced to recognize that there are still bad things happening in the world. Theyd grown too comfortable in their enclosure, most never having to confront not just the zombie horde outside their gates but the rest of the world, other survivors like themselves who might offer difficulties in just staying alive. Rick Grimes (Andrew Lincoln) has shown them this.

As season six opens the group discovers a quarry filled with zombies that could be released at any time and attack Alexandria. Rick and his group devise a plan to release the zombies and direct them in the opposite direction. And of course something ruins their plan and things begin to get dicey. The zombies eventually attack Alexandria. The townspeople discover that they will have to fight to survive this new world.

But this isn't all that happens during this season. In addition to having to deal with zombies Rick and the people of Alexandria learn there are other groups out their trying to survive. One group is the Wolves, a pack like group that attacks and takes from anyone they find. And entire storyline revolves around Morgans capture of one of these attacks that he shows mercy to. Another group are the people of the Hilltop Colony, a peaceful group that they begin trading with. The worst group though are the Saviors who are anything but. Confrontations with this group culminate in perhaps the most intense cliffhanger of all time, one that has been and continues to be talked about to this day in anticipation of the solution when season 7 begins.

This season also offered something different that stirred controversy as some people enjoyed the idea while others hated it. This was an entire episode that discuss just what had happened to Morgan (Lennie James) after Rick and his group left his compound and before he united with the group. The episode ran longer than most and focused solely on Morgan and how he changed from marauding warrior to pacifist before finding Rick again.

But perhaps the most controversial episode involved the fate of Glenn (Steve Yeun). Episode 3 finds him trapped and surrounded by zombies while atop a dumpster with Nicholas. Unable to deal with the situation any longer, Nicholas shoots himself and as he falls drags Glenn off with him. For weeks the shows producers held us in suspense wondering about the fate of Glenn. No spoiler for you if you aren't aware of the outcome but my guess is by now you know. At the time it was the sort of series item that had people talking for week after week. Was Glen alive or not?

The most suspenseful moment though happens in the season finale as Rick and his group go on a road trip with the intent of ending the battle with the Saviors. *SPOILER ALERT*. The group discovers that the Saviors are a much larger group than expected and end up captured. In the last minutes of the show their leader comes out, Negan (Jeffrey Dean Morgan). Those familiar with the character from the comics were sweating this moment out. As each member of Ricks group is forced to kneel in a semi-circle Negan informs them that one of them must pay. He brings out a baseball bat wrapped in barbed wire and the moment slowly pass as he discusses which of them will feel the blows he intends to inflict. We are left with that in the air, a new discussion topic that has people talking months after it aired and an anticipatory public waiting for season 7 to find out the answer.

A few other surprises can be found in this season but I won't reveal them. Instead give this season a watch. Add it to your collection. Discover why I say this is as much a drama series as it is a horror story, possibly more so. Observe and enjoy the display of acting that this show offers, the special effects that will startle most and the story telling that will pull you in and have you waiting for Sundays each week to find out what happens next. Until then watch the series and enjoy it on disc. You won't regret it.

Aside from humans having a virus that turns them into flesh eating zombies, the storyline that stands out for me is how the writers juxtapose the humans who are trying to survive together as a community (Rick's group) against the other groups of humans doing the same thing - surviving. Only difference is which group still retains more of their humanity? The living know that the walkers are dangerous and pretty much grow in numbers - but the real monster - the most dangerous enemy is the living - the ones that want to dominate and remain at the top of the food chain. The Walking Dead is the best series I have ever watched ranking in the top with Breaking Bad, Mad Men, The Good Wife, Game of Thrones & Homeland. TWD will remain as one of the top cult classics ever!

I have a question that has been nagging at me since the first season of Walking Dead. I just finished viewing the 6th season on Blu ray and thought I'd bring up this (probably) tired question of mine: WHY, are there no franchise or corporate names anywhere along the dreary countrysides or even in the cities or small towns from season to season? I have seen minor things like 'goo-goo clusters' shown in season 6 (aren't they a candy staple of The South, and this IS filmed in Georgia). But I'd love to see a deserted or ruined structure that is/was say, a McDonald's, or Denny's, or Starbucks, or Taco Bell, or Ace Hardware, or Safeway Market, the list goes on. Is it because Corporations don't want their properties to be shown in the show, or is it something else? I realize of course this show is all about 'make-believe', but, WHY has there never been any (to the best of my knowledge), big name company featured on the show? I live in a very small town, and there are corporate signs of businesses all over the place. But NOT in Georgia? It would make the show more, I don't know...'realistic' for viewers like me. This is a minor quibble that won't make me stop viewing the show, but I'd still like to know.

First off... I became a big fan of this series over the Christmas Holiday in 2015, where we binge-watched Seasons 1 through 5 on Netflix. Since then, we I picked up Season Six on DirecTV ...  only to find out we only picked up the second half of the season. So, we've been waiting patiently to see this Blu-Ray pop up on the market (or, well, for Netflix to get broadcasting rights to it). This late August, our wish was fulfilled -- however, Amazon's price was over that of our local Best Buy ... so, it was easy to "just go pick it up." So, that's what we did...

Excitement was high, opening the box. It was well constructed and laid out, and not one of those prone to scratching the disc every time you pulled it out of the case, or put it back in for storage. So, that's a bonus. However, running this Blu-Ray on a 4k SUHD screen, it's incredibly grainy (perhaps even more-so than just any of our regular DVDs); the quality simply does NOT appear to be even full HD. Incredibly disappointing, in that regard (enough that we are considering trying to return it).

Overall, however, if you just care about the story and catching up prior to the launch of Season 7... obviously, this is your "best" choice.

I love this show. I think season 6 may be one of the best because of where it goes and how it follows the comic. ::SPOILERS AHEAD::
I love that they introduced the Hilltop, Jesus, Dwight (and giving him a little bit of a backstory and feud with Daryl), how they hinted at The Kingdom, and introduced the Saviors, as well as Negan. Some might think there was a lot of BS with some episodes, like the backstory of what happened to Morgan between "Clear" and the season 5 finale. There were some really epic battles in this season. "The Same Boat" was a real favorite of mine because of how it centered around female characters, and how they were not to be taken lightly. When I watched the finale, I felt like there was a lot of nothing happening, but after watching it a couple more times, I've learned that there was much more to it. It was building up this moment where Rick's group was going to finally realize they're heavily outnumbered and their confidence was about to be pulled out from under them. The cliffhanger was frustrating, but I understand why it happened, and I can't wait for the season 7 premiere.

The 5th season was my favorite season thus far, however the 6th has definitely matched that, if not succeeded it!  There are a couple of slow episodes this season that were kind of frustrating to watch while the season was on TV, however I think I was so frustrated with them only because the storyline was getting so intense and I couldn't stand to wait a week to see the next outcome!  Some of my favorite episodes are from this season now!  "No Way Out", "The Next World" - where something happened that I have been wanting to happen since the 3rd season, but never thought actually would!, "Not Tomorrow Yet"."The Same Boat" and "Last Day on Earth" - This was the most intense 90 minutes of television I have ever watched.  Not because of any sort of crazy action or weird twist, but because they played up the tension the whole episode.  Every commercial break I had to just breath and calm down before it started right back up again.  The acting was superb (especially from Andrew Lincoln who does not get the kind of credit he deserves from all of his amazing performances on this show), so much so that I could just feel the anxiety, worry, and dread coming off of him.  It made me have knots in my stomach.  I love this show and I have never more thoroughly enjoyed  the characters, the writing, the acting, and the storytelling of any other show.

COMFORT ZONES don't exist for the characters of AMCs zombie apocalypse series. There were no comfort zones for viewers in 2016 either. Ratings might have been huge for the finale  17.3 million  but theyve decreased since Season 6. Perhaps because fans don't like being played.

A big reveal promised in previews for the finale was never delivered; it's been saved for Season 7. After an uneven second-half season, viewers rebelled. The outcry has been HUGE.

Producers boast comic book readers have been looking forward to the arrival of new Big Bad, Negan. I found it less spectacular. Negan is just another evil blowhard in love with his own voice. Played by Jeffrey Dean Morgan of Watchmen, Supernatural and The Good Wife, weve seen this before. Do we have to see it  worse, hear it  again?

The first half of TWDs Season 6 is great. Greg Nicotero, master of all things zombie, starts it off with a bang. I kind of went into it thinking it was like a $120-million action movie for considerably less than $120-million, he says in 601 Out of the Quarry, one of six short featurettes.
The multi-episode, multi-perspective story arc has 30,000 extras. No CGI. Rick Grimes (Andrew Lincoln), who got an out-of-character Shane Walsh-persona in Season 5, is a hero again. He learns the current refuge has remained untouched because a barricade has trapped a massive herd of zombies. A plan to lure them away must be implemented before its trial run when the creatures escape first.

It plays like the movie it was intended to be. Extended Episode 604, Heres Not Here featuring Lennie James as Morgan Jones, who returns as a full-fledged cast member, is another standout. It co-stars John Carroll Lynch and is one of the series best.

So hooray for the first nine episodes. The other seven begin badly with 610, The Next World showcasing Rick and Daryl Dixon (Norman Reedus). The comedy approach makes a hash of the characters. They go on a supply run together and, when a truckload is destroyed, they respond with an Oh, well. Thats how it goes attitude. What?!

The next WTH moment arrives via Melissa McBrides Carol Peletier, who suddenly goes pacifist. Through five seasons, the character progressed from a battered wife with a long history of abuse to an empowered champion, able to protect herself and others. Now she deserts her friends. If the change is part of a new story twist, it rings false. Co-executive producer Denise Huth tries to explain it in Strength in Bonds and fails. Where is executive producer Gale Anne Hurd?

No hero likes killing. Carols first triumph came when, Rambo-style, she saves the group from a fortress of cannibals. Early in Season 6, shes a one-woman Assassins Creed, taking on the Wolves, a gang of killers who invade town. So whats with the change? Michonne (Danai Gurira) still retains the title, thank God. But I worry since they're also messing with Daryl. He continues to act out of character in 614, Twice as Far. This man is super-experienced, the groups best warrior and tracker. But his actions all but beg the bad guys to find them. They do, and another new favorite is killed.

Sadly, the five-disc set from Anchor Bay, now owned by Lionsgate, also disappoints. Commentaries promised on the package are missing on disc. They were always among the best features. The featurettes are good; deleted scenes interesting. There is an extended version of the finale, Episode 616, Last Day on Earth if you're up to watching it again. Mini-takes on every episode highlighting stunts and make-up with Nicotero, actors, stunt coordinators and crew are very good. It leaves the impression they still love working on the series.

The 1080p picture is down a few notches from earlier sets, even if it still looks better than broadcast. Color, detail, depth and delineation shine  as usual  among the bonus features. But the overall look of the episodes is fuzzy. Its as if too much film grain has been added to a digital picture. The immersive 7.1 Dolby TrueHD soundtrack continues to be excellent, putting viewers in the heart of the zombie rampage, when Daryl ignites a pool of gasoline or sets off a rocket launcher, and other scenes. There are subtle surround-moments, too, found in deep woods or interior sets. Music continues to set perfect atmosphere.

Not all character changes were unacceptable. Eugene (Josh McDermitt) and Father Gabriel (Seth Gilliam) finally step up. Abraham (Michael Cudlitz) steps down although his one-liners keep coming. Maggie (Lauren Cohan) becomes Alexandras new manager. The ratings drop is barely perceptible in TWDs overall popularity, just enough to notice. I'd rate this 3.5 stars if possible. I hope Season 7 will get us back on target.  Kay Reynolds

The Walking Dead: The Complete Sixth Season begins with Alexandrias safety shattered by multiple threats. The people will have to toughen up while many of Ricks followers will need to take a step back from the violence they had needed to embrace. These reversals won't happen easily, or without conflict. But now Ricks (Andrew Lincoln) group is fighting for something more than survival  they're fighting for their home, and they will defend that at any cost, against any threat, even if that threat comes from within.

The first half of Season 6 deals with an approaching zombie herd and an attack by a rabid band of maniacal predators called the Wolves. Overlapping story lines focus on different characters during the crisis. We also learn Morgans (Lennie James) back story to understand what motivates his no-kill personal code. The second half of the season portrays the survivors as darker and far less moral than in previous seasons, posing the dramatic question, Are these people heroes? The later episodes suggest that a major character has died, for a gotcha cliffhanger.

Bonus extras on the 5-disc, 16-episode Blu-ray release include deleted scenes and several behind-the-scenes featurettes. A digital HD copy is enclosed. Season 6 is also available in a 5-disc DVD edition.

Binge watched this series up to Season 6 in less than 2 weeks. Was afraid to take on something scary but it was done in such a classy way that I soon began to see the 'feared ones' as more of a metaphor. The quality of the writing, the production value, is consistant throughout all seasons, and quintessentially Frank Darabont. These very skilled actors are given real scenes to play, and they are all so unique. Andrew Lincoln seemed like he went way out of his comfort zone and deserves a lot of credit for the success of this series. I felt like I literally watched him grow as an actor.  Loved the diversity of the cast and that they take chances on newcomers whose 'star value' didn't destract me from the story. It tackles some BIG themes and actually changed the way I look at life in so many ways. Can't imagine anyone not taking stock of their life after watching this transforming series. I see now why it has such a loyal fan base. Can't wait for Season 7, and I hope they make it go on forever! I just started rewatching Season 1 and seeing so much more that I missed the first time. What a piece of art.

I didn't start watching The Walking Dead at first because Zombies didn't really do anything for me.  When they had the weekend marathons last year I thought I'd give it a shot and see what all the hype was about.  After watching the first few episodes, I was hooked.  It's not "all" about Zombies.  They play a big role but it's mainly about survival in a hostile world and the relationships between people who have to depend on other people to survive.  The actors and acting is top notch.  It does get a bit bloody at times but it enhances the plot, so it doesn't bother me all that much any more.  I'm 65 years old, so I'm not a kid.  Each season has been great and there are episodes that I like better than others, but even the slow ones give you background on the characters, so I don't mind that.  If you haven't watched it yet, you should definitely give it a shot, but try to watch it from the beginning otherwise you won't understand some of the things that are happening between the characters.

This season was one of my favorites. Finally Rick and company find refuge in a community. Can Rick lead the new community? what decisions will he make?  What consequences will come to the group? Should we kill or should we not kill? The season rolls on to all the moral dilemmas and decisions made  will come at a cost. Rick leads them into battle and they come out victorious. His confidence in the community is restored..but his decision of killing another group could have deadly consequences.  For every thing there is a return, either good or bad. The group now must battle with other groups and a much larger and ruthless group called Negan. The last episode unwinds and they find they are outnumbered and outmatched...how will they adapt to this new group called Negan? This season was good, but I believe next season will be even better. I've liked the storytelling in this show, the moral dilemmas, the camera work, and most of all the characters and the zombies look really realistic. Most people didn't like the last episode in season 6. I liked it and here's why...The show does a great job at making the viewer feel exactly how the characters feel in the show. I felt at the end of the last episode hopeless and in despair and yes torture because we have to wait to see who Negan killed. I first hated this, but now the storytelling will begin with season 7 with a lot to offer..can't wait!

Overall this season really sucked, mostly because it was so frustrating. So many great story telling opportunities wasted. It was also extremely frustrating to watch piecemeal (might not be as painful if you binge watch it). I liked the first 5 seasons overall, but this season the show really lost its way. There were so many potentially great directions they could have taken the story. I thought that the first episode of the season was a real barn burner and looked forward to the rest, but I was sorely disappointed. So many cheesy plot gimmicks, so many random episodes that were just stupid and boring. So many potentially exciting story lines not followed. I thought the whole season was going to be a big adrenaline rush just following the obvious plot setups from the first episode. Instead it wandered off and left us with a very unsatisfying end to the season. I really don't like how the story is becoming more and more like the comic book. I guess the whole thing is based off a comic book, but the earlier seasons seemed more like a survival story, whereas by the middle to end of this season it feels like you are reading a goofy comic book story. Oh well not sure I will invest in the next season. Especially since the show appears to be going completely comic book and focusing on the ridiculous new bad guy.

I want to give 5 stars but I can't.  I love the series, and have since season 1 but the human on human drama and violence is getting to be too much. Get back to dealing with and surviving the zombies being the main threat.

To the makers of the show:  Stop with the drama of good people versus bad people (you have the walking dead as perfectly good opposition) .  Change it up. I was late discovering "The Walking Dead" because I just couldn't envision myself liking a show about zombies. It just sounded too silly.  However, I finally, with reluctance gave it a try, because it had such high star ratings. Also, I knew it was a wildly popular series with several seasons.  To my surprise, I loved it!  A good show can be about almost any topic.

The writing is consistently top-notch.  Every season is as good or better than the one before.. The story is presented in such a way that makes it easy to suspend reality and imagine that it is really happening. The characters are diverse, well fleshed out, and interesting. Despite their flaws, (which make them seem like real people), I found myself really caring about most of them.  The writers were always coming up with imaginative new developments.  Somehow, they  managed to end each episode in a way that  made me impatient to see the next one.

I watched the first 5 seasons on Netflix and purchased season 6 from Amazon.

This used to be one of the coolest 'binge watching' series out there, but the episodes are getting harder and harder to sit through without cringing and scratching my noggin wondering 'why bother', this season in particular ...seems like the writers are playing out the same old scenarios we've seen over and over already. Also, the kid in the cowboy hat gets shot in the eye, next episode, he's fine. The funny doctor lady gets an arrow through the eye, she dead. Seems to me the writers are desperate for plot thickener, but what comes out is dumbly dramatized and sort of insulting. It's hard to get a sense of the bigger picture (where the show is heading), and it seems like the writers are trying to eek out every last speck of boring drama before a conclusion is depicted ...which is unfortunate, wish it felt more about the integrity of the story, less about making money for the crew and cast.

It looks like a lot of folks gave this season positive reviews, to which I say again ...it totally SUCKS that "entertainment" is the overpaid and glamorized influential institution that's too much dumbed-down to meet the lucrative expectations of the least and lessoning of us.

ByDahlgrenon March 30, 2016
Format: Amazon Video|Verified Purchase
After Season 5, which can only be described as the purest possible distillation of the heart of The Walking Dead, Season 6 returns to the lackluster soap-opera seen in prior seasons. The attention to detail has suffered. The writing has suffered. A few characters seem to completely betray what we have come to know as their true selves.

Don't get me wrong, I'll keep watching. I'm a die-hard fan of the series. Just don't expect the same hard-hitting, breathtaking, complex layered storytelling we got last season.

TWD is like Cool Anthropology 101, with evolving social alliances and conflicts within and across groups of survivors.  I look for myself in the characters and wonder who I would be in a zombie apocolypse?  Who would I trust?  How would I spend my efforts and my scarce resources? How would I replenish them?  How would I protect my "stuff and thangs", and how would I protect loved ones?
Now as the story progresses I see that "Who would I be?" is the wrong question. "Being" is stagnant and doomed. The question is "Who would I become?"  I SURE AS HELL DON'T KNOW!  That's why I love joining in on this group's search for its place in an evolving new society.

There is nothing more interesting than this show. I watched all six seasons in 2-3 weeks. Was worth every second. This season, especially, because it has a lot of character development, and a lot of stuff going on within the show. I would've like to have seen more story progression in terms of more information about the virus. Things like how it infected everyone, or why it infected everyone, but I know the story writers are not going to just release the "goods" because I think it would take some added value out of the show. But, they could take a different approach and started talking about the walkers, like research on them as an opponent, such as how long can they live without food, what kind of decay occurs during that time, MORE about why they walk in herds rather than just because of something simple like sound, etc. I really love the show because of the character development, but every 4-5 episodes, it wouldn't hurt to put like a 2 minute skit explaining more about things, give us some of the science-y stuff behind it. That makes it a little more interesting than just "aim for the head" ...

When the series first started, I thought it was about time someone set about a serious look at this zombie phenomenon and what exactly that might look like in the long term. Everyone seems to focus on the first few days and this had promise. Season 1 was funny, clever, and somewhat realistic. People would be stupid, they wouldn't know how to deal with the new reality. But then season 2 came along and it became this running joke of "what you should NOT do in the apocalypse". Failure to set up protocols, properly think about sustainable resources, interacting with strangers etc. It became unintentionally amusing.

But now season six. Here we see magic. Magical bad guys. These people are so dedicated to being evil that they become two dimensional characters. Unbelievable evil spawning with people so DEDICATED to embodying that evil that they'll do anything to continue to be evil, including die for it. That seems to defeat the purpose, since the show just seems to be about the struggle of survival and how much of your humanity you're willing to give up for it.

Then come the hostage scenes. Oh jesus. I'm tired of seeing Rick's Crew be held hostage. They're ALWAYS being captured. It would be one thing if they had adapted and had started learning how to hold out small knives and stuff so they MEANT to be captured, but they don't. The drama is a cycle. Rick and his crew leave the walls, MAGIC BAD GUYS by the billions sneak up to right behind them and put a gun to their head. They NEVER hear them coming, even their hillbilly scout is routinely snuck up on, like watching Worf get beat up over and over again.

And the sheer number of this evil gang nation is ridiculous. They have the ability to block EVERY ROAD with increasingly more bad guys. Sacrifice men in an ambush where they just shoot at their feet, all for the purpose of breaking their spirit when all they needed to do was surround Alexandria with some of that big equipment and some of those MILIONS and MILLIONS of men they're somehow feeding by killing and raiding scavengers and small farms (logistic problem here). It all seems contrived to do nothing but humiliate and torture Rick's group.

If I'd been him, I'd have reacted to the situation that they'd been facing. The bad guys are numerous and somehow operate as if walkers didn't exist. They sneak around the woods looking for people they can bring into their fold or kill. We'd carry that RPG with us everywhere and those displays of force would be big explosions and body parts in seconds. If the enemy has the capacity to overrun us at any moment and kill every one of us or enslave us, then they'd better do it already because if they keep presenting me targets, I'm going to shoot them.

Instead it just seem to be a pissing contest with Rick, who eventually loses. So what's the theme of Walking dead? If the end comes, having any sense of humanity or justice is a sure way to be humiliated, beaten, enslaved and eventually killed. Oh, but being evil is somehow bad too. Even though the obvious paradox of being ruthless and evil that has played itself out throughout history is somehow not present here. No infighting, no devastating civil war as evil guy one and two duke it out for control of said evil empire, just a unified front of evil people willing to die to be evil rather than change their ways and live. Highly organized and high functioning bad guys in a world gone mad.

And what about the zombies? They're a backdrop. Sure, you COULD have a show about how zombies make it harder to farm, get clean water, get supplies, or even be MORE creative and move past zombies to something else, but instead we're left with making humans magical and teleporting them around in front of the "good guys" until... I don't know, it's thematically acceptable for them to jump out and yell "boo"???

In my opinion, this was the best season thus far of TWD. Each episode felt like a finale with the plot twists, character development, introduction of new characters with appropriate cliff hangers and just the right amount of ambiguity to make you want to learn more about them. I purchased each episode at a time, because I wasn't sure if I would be interested enough to watch the entire season. Boy was I wrong. Next time, I'll order the entire season all at once and save myself a few bucks. Highly recommend to all fellow TWD fans and soon to be fans. It's a show that is not only about zombies - if that were the case it would not have lasted this long or held this much growing interest. It's about imagining a post-apocalyptic world - whether that came about by disease, nuclear war, famine, etc. and learning how to survive without laws, government, police, or any type of old world civilization for that manner. It's a conflict on many planes. Man vs. Zombies; Man vs. Nature; and most ominous: Man vs. Man. It is a true testament of man trying to maintain morality, civility, ethics and values when other groups they come across do not share the same POV.

I never liked horror movies, zombie movies, and the like. I found them disturbing; not the way that makes me check under my bed at night, but I just found them to be too creepy and too gory.
A friend of mine pleaded that I really should give the show "The Walking Dead" a chance...so I did...
Was I disturbed?? Definitely..!! Creeped out to no end..??? Absolutely..!
BUT...I started becoming really enthralled with the story, and eventually even became somewhat "numb" to the icky, scary zombies that are awkwardly limping and shuffling around everywhere, with their most disgusting signature-snarl...
The story about the different groups (or sometimes just a single person) of survivors is absolutely gripping. Rick Grimes, Carol, Maggie & Glenn, Daryl, Hershel, Michonne,...they all quickly became "my family" for whom I rooted, feared, felt proud, and/or cried in grief.

This show truly is absolutely terrific, and I am so glad that I listened to my friend and gave "The Walking Dead" a chance. It unreservedly earned it.
Now I'm suffering withdrawal until the next season comes out...

Love it. Don't really watch any TV except for TWD and GOT. This drama keeps me coming back to the screen. The relationships the character's have built amongst themselves as survivors in a cruel, relentless world has me building my own relationship with them. It is highly violent, and I think, as we can ascertain by the season finale, all character's live in equal peril. I love zombies anyway. Zombies are my thing. However, as others have said, this is not a show about zombies. This is an adaption on how to carve out friendships and the healthiest possible survival mechanisms in a world that refuses to allow this. Some episodes are slower than others. I have found, though, when I rewatch these episodes they, dramatically & artfully, have a lot to offer to the viewer.
  I just do not think the actors should be allowed any time off. I want to see TWD all year round. How dare they make me wait until October! I had to take up reading the comic to get my fill.

I loved the way they did the first half of the season, taking place over the span of days. It had some hits and misses, but overall I think it was masterful, and great experimental storytelling. The only "speedbump" was another truly excellent episode "Here is Not Here" which filled in the blanks of a favorite characters return and how he got from where/who he was to the present, more or less. It just felt out of place given the rest of that half of the season.

The second half was far more traditional storytelling with the best episode of the season (and one of the best of the series IMO), 'The Same Boat' and sets the stage for a major characters' moral dilemma that lasts through to the end of the season. They also introduced one of my favorite comic characters in a very "light" (for 'The Walking Dead') episode as we see Ricks outlook after the events from the action packed and stellar second half premier 'No Way Out'.

Where things went off the rails for me, at least, were the final 2 episodes of the season. The "non-cliffhanger cliffhanger" ending of the second to last episode of the season; 'East' (likely due to fan complaints over a plot line from the first half of the season, which is why "Screw the fans." should be rule number one when producing a show like this. Not as in "don't appreciate them", but as in "story comes first, don't cater to fans or engage in fanservice) as a great possible cliffhanger from one episode to the next is blown in a bizarre ending with bad CGI blood-splatter and a line of dialogue in a blacked-out screen that seemed obviously added in post-production so fans of a certain character wouldn't go apoplectic after the first half-seasons' controversial (and IMO great) character's storyline.

The Season Finale itself was stolen by Jeffrey Dean Morgan after a too drawn out and meandering (but effective, it just lasted too long) tension build-up. I can't wait for the uncut version of his speech on Blu Ray. As for the cliffhanger... I have mixed feelings. I knew going in that THAT part of the scene was unfilmable for TV and would likely be POV, which was the best choice, IMO. It was the not revealing who was "it" that irked me. I think the fact of the "New World Order" and total change of power being established was enough of a cliffhanger for me that who was "chosen" could have and SHOULD have been revealed. Those last 2 episodes lose the season 2 stars. Jeffrey Dean Morgan's Season Finale saving, and truly brilliant episode stealing 10-15 minute non-cutaway scene added one star back.

I used to be a Die Hard Fan of this show, but no more. Beware - there will be spoilers as I rant. I fully admit it's a rant. A long rant.

Season 6 took basically everything good about the show and ruined it: plot, character arcs, and most egregiously the impact of the death of beloved characters. Show runners used manipulation and contrived everything from ridiculous character behavior to "cliff-hangers" that went nowhere. Glen's close call became a joke. Then he was surrounded and nearly died again mid-season with another unbelievable save. Nail biting episode endings that never went anywhere sapped all impact from the show: Rick surrounded by walkers as he approaches RV - next episode and he's ahead of the horde nearing Alexandria's gates. Another episode ended with an ominous "help" over the walkie talkie. Next episode...whatever...at some point we see that it was Eugene but not in any kind of meaningful way. Sam calling out for his mom while they are walking through the herd is how the mid season finale ends. Well, we all KNOW that there will be repercussions to that right? Nope. Mid season premiere skips that entirely and sets up a whole new opportunity for Sam to doom himself. Daryl is shot with blood splattering the camera lens at the end of an episode. Oh NO! Oh wait...yeah, no biggie...next time we see him he seems fine. We never actually find out whether he is or not...a little blood on his shirt and he seemed tired...by the time they let us know, if they do, I won't care.

Show runners manipulated viewers throughout the season and every single time, they lost any impact an event might have had. Had Glen escaped in the episode immediately following the one in which we were left hanging, I'd have been interested in his fate. But waiting 4 weeks - and the obvious audience manipulation in that decision - made me not only get irritated at the show, but it made me not care by the time we found out. If there's a cliffhanger now, my reaction is: Well, no reason to care. It either won't be addressed at all going forward or it will take so long to get there that I won't care anymore.

In addition to the cliff-hanger frauds, the characters went from interesting, street-savvy survivors to people wandering around stupidly with contrived motivations and zero story impact. Daryl seemed like a main character in two episodes. Two. And in those he was not given the kind of material the character (or the actor) deserved. In other episodes, if he was there, he was completely out of character. Just how many times do you think sure-footed, expert tracker/hunter Daryl - who knows damn well what the stakes are - is going to get ambushed by a bunch of dudes creeping in the woods?

And Carol - what have they done to Carol? She has been a great character played by a wonderful actor and the recent changes to her story arc have been so contrived and ridiculous that I'm not even thinking about the story (what story?) - the only thing I can think when she's onscreen in the last couple of episodes is "oh, poor Melissa McBride that she had to take Carol in this stupid direction."

Morgan. Morgan was awesome and now he's not. And his most important episode was shoved in between finding out whether Glen was alive or not so instead of enjoying his episode I was irritated and couldn't care less about that particular story. And then they took him too far. Morgan is not stupid. He wouldn't have sacrificed the lives of many to save the life of one....the math doesn't work if his goal is lives saved.

And Rick - Rick rattles from psychotic, to determined leader, to overconfident a$$hole for some reason - oh wait - that's right, they need to get everyone where they need to be for that BIG FINALE that will BLOW OUR MINDS!!

The result is that while they are taking my favorite characters from me through terrible writing, they aren't introducing any new ones worth my time. Abraham, Rosita and Eugene have always come across as caricatures to me and I have never really cared too much about them. Aaron? What happened to Aaron? What happened to his friendship with Daryl? Talk about missed story opportunities. Denise was great and I was so hoping for a great story with her character, but yeah...the Walking Dead narrative is basically bankrupt - they've got no currency but contrived death and dead-maybe-not-dead manipulations. Denise had to go so that Daryl would start the stupid domino crash course for Negan- even though there was no real story there that demanded he do that.

The finale was the last straw for me. The entire season we were promised the most intense, hardest hitting finale ever in the history of TV. But the finale was one more bait and switch in a season full of them. The first 90% was our entire savvy group of survivors getting herded around like rats in a maze and not one of them gave it a second thought. Why on earth would they load everyone into an RV rather than send one fleet-footed person to fetch the doctor? My point is that the writers could have come up with something better than the ridiculous contrived thing that was The Finale. Was J.D. Morgan as Negan impressive? Absolutely. I loved him. I enjoyed about 6 minutes of Negan but it went on for too long and I got bored. And then, finally - all impact was totally sucked from that episode - and the season which lived only to get them to that episode - when they stole that scene from us. Who did they kill? The Show. They killed their show.

I miss Daryl. I miss Carol. I miss Rick. Michonne remains and I love her but her story has stalled in spite of Richonne. Sasha is getting dragged down too. Glen and Maggie haven't been totally lost yet either but Glen's fake death and subsequent near death drained me. I grieved for him already so I don't really care if he lives or dies and Maggie seems peripheral when she shouldn't. Carl is still Carl and that's not necessarily a good thing.

I don't have cable so I've been buying Walking Dead seasons on Amazon. But after this finale I won't be paying for it anymore. There's no point. If I have to wait 6 months to find out who died, why not wait 17, find out if I should even bother, then watch it for free? I certainly won't care less in 17 months than I do right now. Bummer.
