Not many genre series have their best moments five seasons in, but thats how long its taken AMCs The Walking Dead to accrue the history required to deliver an impact more meaningful than just the loss of a fan-favorite character or the letdown when a destination inevitably fails to be what our core group of protagonists had hoped. With four seasons worth of character development informing character interactions and decisions, Walking Dead has molded its characters into a fiercely loyal family thats at once both a force of savage brutality and civility. Having imbued them with such a distrust of outsiders and forced them to adapt to a dangerous world, we now see them face the series hardest question: can they ever really assimilate back into a society? Or will any society that attempts to assimilate them be forced to change to accommodate the mindsets Grimes and company learned out in the wilderness?

After a dull fourth season both teased and dispelled the paradise of Terminus in far too rapid a succession, the fifth season couldn't stand to make the same mistake. This made the introduction of yet another idyllic society midway through the season feel somewhat lazy. Would the writers really repeat the whole this society isn't what it seems concept that theyd already used with the Governor and then Terminus? The Walking Dead had spent the last two seasons harping on the theme that other humans were just as, if not more, dangerous than the zombies that had overtaken the living. Luckily, the fifth season learned from past mistakes and chose to try something new: give the characters something genuinely good and see how they handle it.

Of course, they have to earn it first. In the world of The Walking Dead that means escaping from the prison of Terminus that they ended up in at the conclusion of the fourth season and then miraculously reuniting with the key collection of characters weve come to root for: Rick Grimes (Andrew Lincoln), his son Carl (Chandler Riggs), and katana-wielding Michonne (Danai Gurira); survivalist soulmates Daryl (Norman Reedus) and Carol (Melissa McBride); newlyweds Maggie (Lauren Cohan) and Glenn (Steven Yeun); PTSD sufferer Sasha (Sonequa Martin-Green); and the relative newcomers Sgt. Abraham Ford (Michael Cudlitz), Dr. Eugene Porter (Josh McDermitt), Rosita Espinosa (Christian Serratos), and Tara (Alanna Masterson). Their road to a new civilization is long and marked with an untrustworthy priest (Seth Gilliam), loss, vengeful survivors of Terminus, a detour to save a friend they thought dead, and a drought that threatens to wipe them all out with dehydration.

When the plot finally gets around to the introduction of Alexandria and its community of survivors (11 episodes into the season), were more than ready to see Rick Grimes and his family get a break, unfortunately everything weve followed them through for the past four seasons means every action and word that greets them in Alexandria is met with suspicion. Is the community as genuinely wholesome as its matriarch Deanna Monroe (Tovah Feldshuh) would have them believe? And if so, how has it survived in the modern world of scavengers and zombies?

Alexandria presents the most interesting scenario for The Walking Dead since the first season, and the writers smartly take their time letting characters reveal facets of the society, its imperfections, and the ways that it is exactly what Deanna claims. For once were given a scenario where the most sinister villain isn't the hidden intentions of a secretly evil populace but rather the frustrations and naivet of a group of people whove lived so long inside of a bubble that they're unaware of how bad things have gotten on the outside. Watching Rick Grimess crew quickly step into leadership roles (by fighting off a horde of the undead from a construction site, or search for survivors in the wild) is a richly satisfying outcome for the characters after all theyve been through, but its not without its share of genuinely fear-inducing moments as one of the series best characters goes head-to-head with one of Alexandrias more cowardly inhabitants in the woods. The conclusion of the season signals more growing pains ahead for Alexandria as well as a return to the norm for the series as a new band of scavengers is introduced as the likely foes for the sixth season.

As a final note: few moments in this season were as sublime as the return of Lennie James as the incredibly badass, staff-wielding Morgan Jones. His most triumphant scene both highlighted how much hes changed in the years since Rick Grimes left him in Atlanta and the kind of people our heroes will be facing next year.

Blu-ray Bonus Features

The Blu-ray set includes the entire season as an Ultraviolet digital copy, as well as an impressive number of featurettes covering the production, the creation of Alexandria, supplementary materials on how Beth, Bob, Noah, and Tyreese got to where they were, days on set with Michael Cudlitz and Josh McDermitt, and a piece on the zombies themselves. Audio commentaries and deleted scenes are also included.

Season six is quite possibly my favorite season after the original, but I think Season 7 will change that later this year. Seasons four and five really dragged for me to the point that I almost gave up on it, but I was intrigued by the last half of season five when they found Alexandria. Season six had a lot of action, suspense, and controversial cliffhangers. This review will contain some spoilers!

The group must not only deal with over 1,000 zombies trying to invade Alexandria but they have to fight off more evil groups of people such as the Wolves and the Saviors. Morgan was given his very own solo episode that shows why throughout this season he lives by his 'All life is precious' motto, but the action and storytelling make up for it. My top 3 favorite episodes are JSS when the Wolves attack and Carol really steps up her 'Rambo' game, Not Tomorrow Yet when Rick leads a full on assault against a group of sleeping Saviors, and Last Day on Earth, the hugely controversial episode that ends on a massive cliffhanger. Rick Grimes steps into a much larger world when he meets Paul Rovia, who goes by the nickname, Jesus. Jesus leads Rick and his people to the Hilltop where they learn about the Saviors and their leader, Negan. Negan may very well be the toughest adversary Rick and his group has faced yet. If you love the show, I highly recommend THE WALKING DEAD: THE COMPLETE 6TH SEASON!!!

Deeper than its given credit for, the show parks itself in a laboratory of human emotion and ethical dilemmas. The question of ethics and pragmatism is always being played out: what's right in a world gone wrong, where the moral compass has been swept away by the bare need to survive; find food...hope...life...love...and when all the above is threatened or taken away: vengeance.

The season finale removes the floor and drops the viewer down an elevator shaft, all too familiar but has it ever been this dark? Have the stakes been so high?

It's the ultimate and undeniable question of the survival of the fittest, and as some despair to ask: survive for what? The entire show is a study in the metanarrative of ultimate questions we all live in: what are you living for? Why? Who determines right and wrong - is it always, simply, the biggest bully?

Personally, I can't wait for next season. But the finale leaves you breathless.

I loved this show, couldn't wait till the next episode/season... until now.  This season is so all over the place.  I don't know how they got from A to B in this season. The plot lines are hard to follow which makes it difficult to care what happens next, which I pretty much don't, anymore.  So the writers and directors can make it as far fetched as they want, changing the cinematic style anytime they feel like it, up the violence every season, threaten or kill any of the best characters just for the shock value of it, jump over plot-hole after plot-hole like they honestly can't see them.  I won't complain, cause I am not anticipating this show anymore.  They lost me.  To bad too, cause I was really very interested in how it would work out for the group before season 6.  But then they came across a humongous group that happens to be made up solely of every surviving bouncer (they were all huge and so mean looking. How did they all end up in the same place? Weird.) in the world.  I just had to roll my eyes and say, "Why didn't those guys simply go to Alexandria in the first place?"  And what's up with Daryl's dirty greasy hair in absolutely every episode.  I don't understand why that would be the hair choice, honestly?
Anyway, maybe I'll see how it ends up when it gets to Netflix, but I think a better way is to just ask someone who's seen it. I'll get the same result without the frustration and irritation of watching this bloody, violent, aggravating show anymore.
On the up side, the acting is still great and I do like the characters.  The cast is amazing and does continue to get better.

I love The Walking Dead, however, Season 6 went south and never made a comeback. As any true fan knows, the series was never about the zombies; they were simply part of the environment but posed a constant and horrifying threat to the living. Many of the early reviews panned The Walking Dead for the zombies' limited role but I didn't find it a problem. However, after the zombie-slaughterfest prompted by the loss of Rick's latest love interest, there are virtually no zombies left. The few that remain are nothing more than an afterthought and I would now agree that the show's premise has been undermined. Without zombies in the mix, the show is more of a soap opera revolving around the romances which blossomed over the course of six seasons. I am assuming that the show's writers are sci-fi and horror specialists because that would explain the wooden, sterile and awkwardness one feels watching the new couples in bed. The season finale is next week and I pray for redemption; otherwise I don't see the need for a seventh season.

Although there were one or two decent episodes this season, overall, this is the worst season yet. Episodes 14 and 15 reached an all-time low. Walking Dead has created many interesting characters, but for some reason the writing staff doesn't know what to do with them. Often the characters, instead of gaining depth, are forced by the writers to act totally out of character. Interesting possibilities are often cut short by an arbitrary death or an unlikely change in development while at the same time the tired plots retread the same ground over and over again. Angela Kang is the best writer of the group. Show runner, Scott Gimple, on the other hand, is clueless and needs to be replaced, and Robert Kirkwood needs to be told to stick to his comic books and leave what was once an intriguing show alone. My advice: Bring back Frank Darabont.

This was, in a sense, a quieter season before a another storm hits. I find myself wondering as a show fan, rather than a comic book fan (sorry, all you purists), is it necessary to follow the story line laid out in the books quite so...'fan-natically" (pun intended). I enjoy some of the quieter moments, the little moments where characters take a breather and you actually get to watch a character's growth and inner struggles. I especially enjoyed those moments this season. I'd like to see more of an actual community building and those challenges, instead of, yet again, it seems running up against another tyrannical, power mad maniac leader. I really hated seeing the end of Denise and the apparent Maggie mis-carriage, etc. The acting itself if you enjoy character building really went up a notch. The yanking the rug from out under the feet every time something is going good is getting a little old with yet another crazed tyrant  - even for the end of the world

This show is truly incredible!  I don't like those shows where there is no character development or character consistency; those shows that go back and forth on who should be with whom (because that's super important, right?), and the ones with no plot line.  The Walking Dead is nothing like that.  Because it's a group of people in the worst of circumstances, their true selves are constantly being revealed.  As a result, character development is huge.  It's so interesting to see how the people's experiences change and mold them in different ways than their companions.  In the beginning you've got a scared little lady who becomes the biggest freaking badass around.  You've got the person who joins the apocalypse a little late and is reluctant to kill, and he develops so much that he rips a guy's throat out with his TEETH with no hesitation in order to save his family.  The directors are not afraid to kill off characters, and while it's heartbreaking most of the time, it means the characters are never stagnant.  Nobody is safe, and it keeps you on your toes.  This isn't just a zombie show.  It's a story of epic proportions, of the people surviving together, fighting against the dead, the living, and circumstances.  The best and worst parts of people are revealed when everything around them falls apart.  This show is amazing.

This has gone from an exciting fun to watch action show to a run of the mill soap opera drama. The lengthy character and plot development is difficult to sit through. The unrealistic creature comforts the characters enjoy are downright silly; the shower scene, in ep. 15 "East", with Glen and Maggie, as an example, is hard to believe. They really have that huge luxury shower with endless hot water after the zombie apocalypse? Or gas for cooking large feasts, or power for refrigerators! The early seasons were more realistic, which I found enjoyable. On a positive note I do think the production is good. Maybe binge watching the sixth season would be a better experience, but the traditional episodic presentation has me looking for other shows to watch.

As the series has evolved, the overall quality of the show has declined. The world created by the original comic books has been shown to be a fertile environment for drama, action, and conflict (man v man, man v environment, man v self). Yet as we move from season to season,  the writers have struggled to maintain the same level of adrenaline pumping excitement which was injected to our collective consciousness with the first season.  And that makes sense.  It's the "Home Improvement" effect, Tim Allen is good at telling jokes, but after the first couple episodes we see the same shtick every week.  This is where TWD writers are now, they stuggle to give us something new and it shows in the faux drama created in the relationships.  Don't get me wrong, this is a hard thing to do as a writer, but it can be done (e.g. BBC's Sherlock).  Unfortunately,  TWD writers go for awkward and contrived scenarios which leave characters not reacting as we would expect a seasoned apocalypse survivor to react just so they can get caught by competing groups for the sole purpose of serving the plot. The show has transitioned from the living fighting to survive to a lawless soap opera with the occasional undead attack and a plethora of self aggrandizing monologues. I think there is an intentional move to that type of show. TWD execs know their core audience and the most fervent fans are quick to bear their emotions regarding the plot lines and criticism of where the show is going. All one has to do is read any social media thread regarding the character of Daryl Dixon (Norman Reedus) and you get a sense of the maturity level of those who express their opinion and their disdain for those who disagree. In the end, I can't fault TWD for feeding the trolls, it is a good formula for longevity,  but that does not guarantee the quality of the writing.

It's become a medicore soap opera with zombies as a backdrop. At least in other zombie-based drama / horror movies the zombies evolve somehow and become a dynamic part of the narrative.  Given the sycophantic praise for this show I don't expect my comments to make much of a dent but wanted to express my disappointment with this show. It's become a carousel of temporary characters many of whom last for one or maybe two episodes while the main characters alternate between pacifism and rage. That's been going on since Season 1 and it's amazing how little the primary characters have evolved. Sure, they have some episodes dedicated to explaining the back story of individuals as a way to take a break from the action but the characters. Yes I understand that it loosely follows the comic book series although watching them repeat the same mistakes is wearing thin as there is no development - just variations on a limited number of themes.

What can I say? A lot. I am a Dostoievski, Coelho,  F. Herbert, Faulkner,  Marquez, LaHaye and other great authors lover. I like science fiction and true or fictional stories in the same measure. But zombies?  A few years ago, one of my very good friend told me about The Walking Dead. I wondered how could anyone like zombie movies. I was just arrogant and now I feel really bad. I will never again say that I don't like anything before trying it. Because The Walking Dead is awesome! !!! I saw the first 5 seasons on Netflix in less than 2 weeks!  I couldn't do anything else but watching!  I like each caracter in particular,  for different reasons. I can't say anything negative,  eventually I can say that I hope that it will continue as long as possible. Give it a try, even if you think that zombies are ridiculous. The interactions between the living characters is so powerful, the fight for survival shows the bad but also the good part of our human nature. I just love it. Try it!

Is it just me, or does this series just keep getting better ? Most series' hit a peak and then start fading away by now, but this series (season six) the situations and characters never stop evolving. The writers for this show should get a medal or something! And the quality of the camera work, the acting (which is great) the professional sound, the director is brilliant, and last but not least, HOW DO THEY MAKE THAT STUFF LOOK SO REAL!? If it's not CGI, then these guys have made an art of making all the zombie bashing look so real that I actually gasp out loud sometimes! YIKES! The action never stops. The gore is horrifying (but in a good way)...This series reminds me of other fantastic titles, like Justified, or Supernatural (and a select few others) they just keep drawing you in. Everyone I know watches this show. I was looking for something good to watch and my son said The Walking Dead is about the BEST series he's ever seen. Soooo, I started watching it from the first episode, and then I binged all the way to season four and paid for the 5th.... I. Was. Hooked. Bad! We're caught up (dang) and now were waiting for the next episode. And Glen better NOT be dead or I my wife will have a caniption fit!!
SPOILER:This review is for fans that are probably freaking out as bad as I am. Glen is alive! My wife is very happy; when Glen finally crawled out from beneath that dumpster she as punching me in the arm (ouch) and shouting: Ooo! Ooo! I TOLD YOU! I TOLD YOU !!! Honestly, I'd already heard rumors. I'd heard that fans were going to riot, and start a mutiny if Glen was gone. Okay....whew...good one that! But all of a sudden Rick and the "family" are running out of supplies. They're slowly starving, BUT THEN. Rick and Darrell meet a guy....Jesus. Yes, I said Jesus. A guy named Jesus. But this Jesus, (a regular guy) might turn out to be the answer for our desperate heroes? Turns out, not so much. Once again. The writers change gears near midseason.
UPDATE!!!
OMG!!! Did everybody see this ending?!?! WTH! I'm freaking out! Who just got their head.... oh, man!!! Nope...not gonna do it...I just can't potentially spoil this for somebody. But...OH MAN! Does this show freaking rock, or what!? (rhetorical question) The actors, the writers.. BRAVOOOO! (Lots of clapping)
CANNOT WAIT FOR NEXT SEASON

Request to cancel season pass: I recently opened a chat with Amazon customer service (then won't let u email them) about how dissatisfied I am that TWD episodes went from being released around 10 pm (I live in Hawaii) to 3am. To me this is a very significant change in the product I paid for and had I known about this change in release time in the fall, I wouldn't have purchased it. This is what I sent to amazon:

Hi I would like to cancel the remainder of my order for The Walking Dead Season 6. When I purchased this season in the fall, the episodes would be realeased around 10pm Hawaii time which is not too late for me since I am a fan of the show. Lately, however the episodes are not released until about 3 a.m. Had I know about this change in release time I never would have ordered the season. You have changed the product you sold me with notice or compensation. Please cancel the rest of the season pass for me. Also please refund the episode I purchased on February 29. The episode was available for single purchase but not to season subscribers, and I read that you would refund those kinds of purchases. Anyway I think you should revamp how you get all those episodes out. It is very frustrating to be a SD season pass holder. I have to wait usually an hour, first as the HD episode is released, then the SD episode, then the HD season pass is available, then finally I am allowed to watch what i signed up for months ago.

The Walking series gives us credible characters with needs, fears, weaknesses and strengths like the people we see around us everyday. It's when the going gets tough that some either find a way to be stronger or they struggle and need help or become lost. Rick Grimes and everyone else must face hard choices and sometimes insanely difficult choices. I can't help but wonder how I would handle it if the choices were mine. The cast are fine examples of solid, competent actors. There is no over-acting that can distract from the drama unfolding. Those people, young and old, do such a good job bringing people that I care about to life. And in this story line there are people who make mistakes and need to be forgiven and when they find forgiveness and peace the drama hits a high point. Yes, the idea of a zombie apocalypse is weird. I agree. But it is what the people do and how they handle themselves that makes The Walking Dead a drama series that I respect.

Both the plots in Season 5 and Season 6 of The Walking Dead have seemed exceptionally slow moving. It's not that I expect the show to be action -packed, with lots of blood and gore, I am perfectly content with a slower moving show, so long as something is happening.

I feel like the writers lack either the imagination or the capability of bringing some resolution to the series. What do I mean by that? Well, allow me to explain. I can summarize most seasons in the following manner: new crazy bad guy ---> people split up ---> multiple episodes where nothing important happens --> epic episode where the main characters save the day ---> somebody dies ---> repeat. Every season follows, more or less, this structure. Ever since the beginning of the show, I have been looking forward to the day when advancements were made that could help return the planet to some form of normality. Early on, there were a few seasons were I really thought that was what the show was going to be about: a group of people that, against all odds, build a life for themselves in the midst of utter social breakdown. When the crew was heading to the CDC and Washington D.C., for example, the writers portrayed the main characters as having, potentially, the power to make a big difference. Lately though, the same fundamental plot line keeps repeating, and it is getting boring.

Sure, the writers have tried to spice things up by killing off characters and bringing new ones on. Yes, the writers have introduced new romances and new dramas. Those things don't appeal to me in the long term. They spike my adrenaline in the moment, but do little else.

I guess what I am saying is that it would be nice to see something drastically different happen.

I still love the series, but if the episodes remain as slow going as they are now, I don't know how much longer I will be watching it.

I came late to this party - just tried it this year and binge watched from the beginning. I have to say it's the most enjoyable television show that I've ever watched. The story is beautiful in its raw emotion, how it strips down everyone physically and emotionally, forcing the characters to live life perhaps how it should be lived: in the moment, urgent, thankful for every moment of life. These characters get inside your heart and stay - their evolution or devolution keeps the storyline fresh. The backdrop of chaos, gore, blood and a broken world contrasts with the beauty and dignity of this band of lost souls and their poignant struggle to find or keep those characteristics alive in themselves. The well-chosen songs and the soundtrack further enhance the mood, providing a voice for the characters where words sometimes fail and never distracting from the overall theme of the episode. I see flaws, but I can forgive them, and they don't change my overall enjoyment of this adventure. I'm along for the ride now and can't wait to see where we're going next.

The only thing keeping me going at this point is the memory of the character I love.  But honestly, I find myself more let-down than ever after each new episode.  The unique-ness of the characters is slowly being whittled down and I am seeing them all become the same.  I feel like writer's or maybe its the director, who knows, has an agenda.  Like someone working on this has a strong opinion about certain issues and that agenda is bleeding through on EVERY character.  Everyone is becoming the same and predictable.  This can often happen in writing and I think the writer's are falling into this mistake.  Its turning the show into a statement that reflects a person's set of beliefs and its causing all the stories, side stories and characters to morph into the same thing and honestly, its just growing stale.

Want to love this, but just can't.  The direction of the show has degraded slowly over the seasons and we see more of the writer's own personal philosophy and agendas taking over all of the characters as if they all have one mind.  I have finally decided its just not worth watching anymore.  Half way through this season, I realized I really just can't care about what happens anymore.  I want to, but the characters aren't true to themselves anymore.  They're all the same.  And for the few that seem like their own characters, well, the show goes about with the single objective of bringing them down to the cliched atheiistic pessimistic mold that the writer's have conformed every unique soul too.  Anyone who deviates from this is portrayed as a complete stereotyped moron.  The writer's could stand to back off on their agendas and let the characters speak for themselves again.  Move on to better pastures....  Its run its course.

Taking my review down to a 4... here is why.

Great show, but why is our original cast not learning new techniques on how to defend there home.  Also, why are there so many flaws to their strategies.

I am also a little irked at the "coincidences" that keep occurring.  I would get the tractor hitting the wall at just the right time if the W's were watching... but they were not.  It was just a coincidence.  And to just happen to land on the horn... CMON!

I am also VERY irked they are not killing some of our main characters, that is one of the reason the show is so dang good.  I mean, they dangle it, they tease it, then they pull it back like chickens.  CMON!!  Part of what makes this great is we never know who is going to bite it.  Don't get me wrong, I really enjoy our main characters, but its time to rip one from us, make us Cringe!

Zombies, zombies and zombies and we are still getting bit?  Idiots.
Also, doesn't it bother you that they are driving junker cars.  Why in the heck haven't they found some really good vehicles, armored trucks and such, instead of this garbage they are driving.  Its not 40 years later, its a couple years, those things should be all over the place!

Don't get me wrong, I love the show, but they really need to act like they are learning, or whats the point of experiencing the same thing over and over again and not getting better at dealing with it?

Unfortunately, I sense the end coming- not soon- and my greatest hope is that they end on a high note. I know that sounds ridiculous, but it could be done. The day this went up for pre-order I did just that, pre-order it.  I have all the previous collector's sets and they have been fantastic purchases over the years.  I expected this to be the same.  But this is lackluster at best.  I am very disappointed in this collector's set.  It's a plastic "statue" you could find in any comic shop for $40, but here I spent $135.  Normally pre-order sets drop around to 40% off a month before it gets shipped out, but not this one.  But I was dedicated to ordering it.  When I opened it finally I was underwhelmed and regretted the purchase.  The paint job also looks very muddy.  I know it's supposed to be blood and gore, but just feels like some random colors were shoddily mixed together and poured onto the "statue".  I feel like I'm stuck with it now, but I'm going to be wary and more critical of any future release TWD puts out.  A shame, they were doing so well until this set.

The Walking Dead is something that you either get, or you don't. Season six part one explores group dynamics in a fairly new way, with the integration of new characters that are pivotal in some forthcoming events. It opens hard and carries some great underlying tension that isn't fully resolved at mid-season finale, but hints at where it's going. This is the season where a lot comes together. Sure there are plenty of icky Walker scenes, but the story itself has a purpose.

If you're a viewer who's still looking at the show as zombie schtick... this season, in particular, will be lost on you. If you understand who the "walking dead" really are, you'll be looking forward to the second half of the season. If you've not explored this show but have dialed it up because your buddies are going on about it, you really need to take a slow weekend and work your way through the series from episode one. A key aspect to enjoying the program is immersion the background on the experiences that inform the decisions of the characters.

As a programming note to newbies: the show splits its air dates into two halves, fall is first half with a mid-season finale that ends in time for the holidays, and it picks back up again in February for another six to eight episodes. As of posting date this would be the first half of season six so you'll have to catch the rest live on amc or here on amazon usually the day after it airs.

Unfortunately not a great season overall. "Here's Not Here" was an excellent story in itself that gave viewers philosophical gristle to chew on while they await the next episode, and "JSS" featured a number or wonderful moments (watch how the kitchen timer marks a return to normalcy after the Wolf attack)...but other episodes were marred by plot holes and glaring inconsistencies in the reactions of the main characters.

The series is largely stuck in a stimulus-response loop that has dominated previous seasons, preventing any real progress in the story line.  But the largest disappointment of all was the teaser surrounding Glenn's death. The initial shock of seeing him on the ground surrounded by walkers becomes disbelief, and then dark comedy, when another episode opens and we see him facing 180 degrees from his earlier position, with Nate's body in a completely different position than logic suggests.  It was sloppy work, and I was reminded of a scene in Misery when Kathy Bates' character compare's James Caan's sloppy writing to a serial she saw as a child

  "The bad guy stuck him in a car on a mountain road and knocked him out and welded the door shut and tore out the brakes and started him to his death, and he woke up and tried to steer and tried to get out but the car went off a cliff before he could escape! And it crashed and burned and I was so upset and excited, and the next week, you better believe I was first in line...And there was Rocketman, trying to get out, and here comes the cliff, and just before the car went off the cliff, he jumped free! And all the kids cheered! But I didn't cheer. I stood right up and started shouting. This isn't what happened last week! Have you all got amnesia? They just cheated us! This isn't fair! HE DID'NT GET OUT OF THE COCK - A - DOODIE CAR!

After the mid-season finale -- absolutely best season yet so far, and it can only get better.  And my motto for life is now "JSS" -- "Just Survive Somehow".  Enid and Nicholas (yes, that a-hole) were my favorites this season so far, besides all the regulars and semi-regulars (Go Jessie!).  SPOILER:  I was blown away by Nicholas' "Thank you" in Episode 3 -- even a-holes, ESPECIALLY A-HOLES, can sometimes redeem themselves before it's too late, which I guess is what Morgan is trying to get across.  In the end, Nicholas had his self-respect back again due to Glenn's ability to see him as a person, and that is why The Walking Dead is such a lesson for life on so many levels.  I was simply floored by that scene -- you could see that Nicholas' gratitude was the last thought on his mind before he pulled the trigger.  Glenn may later have more time to reflect on that moment, but in that instant, Glenn nearly paid the price for his forgiveness, as others may also have done and may yet do because of Morgan's life philosophy (we shall see).  But one can never say that The Walking Dead is ONLY about walkers and bad guys going after the good guys -- it's about LIFE and life's choices, and how do you live that life, before, during, or after a brutalizing, de-humanizing apocalypse of any kind?  I can't foresee ever turning my back on the Rick Grimes character; he's no angel, but he's certainly no devil.  Just a darn steadfast human being and father to boot.  If not for him, a whole lot of people who are alive now and have a game plan for survival would not be, and would not have.  Long live Rick, long live them all!

Great drama, but very unrealistic.(Zombies aside.) Everything, goes wrong for the main characters all the time. It is bad enough that they live in world full of zombies, but there bad luck only begins there. A typical example would be they find a wall city, great news right? Wrong, the zombies are nearby in a huge pit, so instead of killing and burning them where they are, they decide to lead the zombies 20 miles away. (about a 10 hour walk from their city.) Of course, just when this is happening, a group of other survivors decide to attack the city. And of course they don't do it quietly, so a truck is left with its horn stuck on to attract the zombies they are trying to lead away. After defending the city, buildings near the city were left burning, and one tower decides to fall down and break a hole in the wall large enough for thousands of zombies to fill the town in a matter of minutes. (There was only a 1 in 4 chance it would fall tall the city) The odds the  other survivors would attack the city when they did, leave the horn blasting as long as it did, and the tower falling over the wall in one afternoon are astronomical. The speed of which slow walking zombies found their way between a burning building and the wall was amazing. Awhile this all happen yet other members of the main cast are ambushed along the road, apparently by a motor cycle gang just waiting on the road for people to rob.(What are the odds of that happening?)  These people are all going to die, not because of zombies, but because they have horrific luck, and bad problem solving skills.

My husband and I started watching this when my daughter was in nursung school in Texas.  She is discerning; we trust her judgement, so we watched here in Maine, and had wonderful discussions with her the next day.  I am impressed with the strong women, with the literary, cultural, and mythical references.  I am pleased that the elderly and young are shown to rise to selflessness, and courage alongside the adults in their prime.  The possibilities of human nature are explored and on full display.  This season rather than have aggressively evil figures such as the governor, or the sanctuary crew, we watched the struggles of the "regular folk" Alexandrians as the presence of Rick et al challenged their precarious community code.  Not enough Daryl this season; too much Morgan.  He hurt Carol.  Done with him.  I did not quite believe the scene in the season finale when Tara and Rosita burst in upon the "wolf" and his hostage. Unlike some reviews and blogs, I did enjoy the episodes in Alexandria, and I continue to be a fan of Rick.  I think Andrew Lincoln as created an iconic, modern day John Wayne type of character, but more along the line of Wayne's troubled, brooding Ethan in the "Searchers".

BRAVO TO THE CAST WHO acted their parts so well, to the directors and producers for knowing how to interpret what the writers intended for us to see. AAAAAAH! I LOVE THIS SERIES! I swear, if this show ends, and it will, I don't care if zombies rule the world because what would be the point of living?

This should be called The Tedious Living because basically the scripts are all predicated on the idea that viewers aren't going to engage their grey matter but instead will just gape with mouths open at the endless "action" sequences that intersperse what is essentially yet another soap opera.

Naturally anything with zombies occupying a central plot role isn't going to rely on verisimilitude but TWD takes audience credulity beyond any limit. Want to blow up a tank? Roll a grenade down the barrel (yes, really...). Want to recycle the endless lame "drop your guns, slide them over to me" routine? Oh yes. Brave band of survivors apparently unable to run without tripping at the most inopportune moments? You betcha. Hollywood rounds (my favorite so far, a 9mm with a 15-round mag that fired 23 shots without requiring a reload) in abundance. And a complete lack of situational awareness coupled to total cluelessness about how to move across contested terrain? Yes sir!

So in short this is a series for people who want to stroke their shotgun barrel while sitting on the sofa eating popcorn and imagining how they'd fare if the zombie apocalypse ever arrived. Fortunately no one suffers from toothache or appendicitis or any other medical problem. Amazingly none of the characters needs any sort of regular medication despite the real-world fact that US citizens are basically addicted to pharmaceuticals and, thanks to the obesity epidemic, would drop dead within days without access to a pharmacy. In this little violent fantasy world in which unskilled civilians double-tap like highly trained SEALs, life is basically pretty good.

If you like real-world human drama that may actually teach you something this series is best avoided. There are better parodies out there than this seemingly endless self-parody. But if you love watching people shooting at the undead (so much more politically correct than some real-life alternatives that were on offer in the USA not so long ago) and don't mind scripts that are as stale as the zombies themselves (trust me, some of these scenes really truly stink) then why not pull up a chair and sleep through an episode or two?

The premise of the series (not just the season) is that of a world infested with the living dead. Its a theme that probably goes even father back than Richard Matheson's 'I am legend', with actors like Will Smith and Charton Heston gracing the solitary landscape at various times in cine history. Its a theme thats haunting, chilling and immensely absorbing. Its a 'what-if' world. While there have been takes and retakes, hits and misses, tongue in cheek spoofs, as in ZombieLand, nothing to date comes close to this extremely gritty, taut and well directed series. While it was easy to have brushed past the average beginnings to this series, I hung in there through the first season, and was amply rewarded by this edge of the seat AMC TV Series. It is macabre and gruesome, but if you can stomach all that, you will find the acting, story and direction superb. The chemistry amongst the characters is strong with the good and bad characters playing their roles to almost perfection, and eventually blurring what little separates the two. The brooding Norman Reedus, the tortured and conflicted Andrew Lincoln, and the entire cast play their roles with so much conviction its hard not to believe such a world as we seem them in cannot exist sometime in the future.

The only reason I knock off a star is because the show overplays  the human emotional interplay and underplays the science and logic that might have added an interesting twist to the theme.

Still love The Walking Dead, even though some "fans" are saying they "jumped the shark" with the "is Glenn dead or isn't he?" shenanigans.  In my opinion it's all in good fun and didn't make me feel like I was being treated like I was stupid in the slightest.  It's meant to be entertainment, after all.  If it makes you feel stupid, don't get your undies in a wad, just don't watch it.  But I'm not sure how enjoying an entertaining TV show can make you feel stupid.  You may want to pretend you're watching some Shakespearean play because of the serious and deep subject matter, along with the great acting, but let's face it; it's a soap opera!!  Albeit, a zombie soap opera, but it is still a serial where you get emotionally involved.  I'm GLAD Glenn survived the Nicholas fiasco; he didn't deserve such an ignominious death and he's one of my favorite characters.  I know they'll be plucking them off one-by-one, but I will likely be watching until the "last man is standing" (Daryl?  Or maybe it will be Judith or Carol, and not a man at all?)  Hopefully they will be able to continue telling us interesting stories about our favorite zombie apocalypse heroes for some time to come.

02/2018 EDIT:  I loved this show for a long time, but now I think they've killed it.  Glenn was the heart of the show.  Everything about the show has gone downhill since they brutally killed him off.... and for what? To keep to the comic book? They've strayed from that before and the reason was that this is TV, not a comic book. This used to be a compelling story about characters that felt real in an unreal situation. Now, for some reason they have decided to write the characters we used to love as caricatures. And killing off Carl?  Another stupid move.  Figure it out showrunners and writers! Otherwise you can stick a fork in this once great series.

I love this show so much!!! To be honest, when this show ends I honestly won't know what to do with myself. My Sundays will be so blah. Lol But in my opinion, out of the seasons so far, season 6 started off with an incredible bang, and for me, and it is the second best season out of the entire series. But on the emotional front, my gosh! This season is leading on the emotional end. You really don't know what to expect from each episode. I'm finding myself on edge, practically waiting for Sundays to come. I start counting down the days as soon as a new episode finishes, and then on the day of the new episode, I count down the hours and then the minutes....like...It's really bad! Every episode has its own flavor and story to tell within the entire seasonal arc. I must say for season six I have been experiencing intense emotional manipulation from some of the episodes! I started off excited, then I was left with fear .Then I felt hopeful which led me to dread. And while I'm still feel down, I'm feel horrified about what's going to happen next. Gah! I love this show. I love this season and I can't wait to see what else in store for the rest of the season!

It is becoming increasingly obvious to me that season 6 is the best season of The Walking Dead(TWD). What should also be clear is the that this show might be the best drama on television today. No, I am not a fan of zombies, zombie movies, or horror film. That being said TWD is living up to the poster I read once concerning the show 'kill the dead, fear the living'. The drama comes from the human beings trying to survive. I started watching the show because I didn't want to be an adult afraid of elaborate make-up and special effects. I now find myself at work on Sundays wondering what one human being will do,or have to do, to another in order to survive.

The BEST show on television EVER!! If the 90 minute episode featuring Lennie James (Morgan) doesn't win any type of Emmy award, either for best writing, directing, best lead actor performance, etc.then the whole system is rigged!  Lennie James DESERVES an Emmy Award for his performance in that episode!! This show is not all about horror and zombies, although, yes, that is a big part of it, however it's REALLY about the characters, their story lines, where they came from, how they have changed...It's definitely a character-driven show. That's why we get so upset when they kill off a beloved character (still can't believe they killed off Andrea, Beth, Hershel and now possibly Glenn) with Maggie being pregnant and all. I want to at least know that Glenn knows he's becoming a father. I sure hope Maggie is able to give birth naturally without any complications like Lori had. Hate to say it but in that post walker/biter/roamer-apocalyptic world, maybe it will be a blessing if she has a miscarriage... I know a lot of fans might not like hearing me say that, but just trying to be realistic about such a bleak future it would be for pregnant women during that time. Oh, so much more to write about! I could go on and on. I watched a marathon of the first 3 seasons on Netflix even though I've already seen every episode multiple times before, just wanted a refresher since my memory of the earlier seasons gets a little hazy at times. There are things I've missed before that was worth a second look at the past episodes.

The only drawback with some of the writing is a few noticeable inconsistencies, the first one going back to Season 1 where Rick doesn't know how to hot wire that car so he takes the horse into Atlanta instead, which quickly gets devoured by walkers. Then later, he is able to hot wire a car for Glenn to drive off back to camp with the car alarm blaring...huh? Or when after Lori dies at the prison, Rick bloodies and sweat a lot by slaughtering countless walkers to find Lori's remains, then in the next scene, he is completely cleaned up with a fresh set of clothes on, huh?

I am really anxious and excited for Rick to have a new love interest in Jessie. I just hope for Rick's sake she stays alive for awhile or he'll grow even colder. He needs a good woman like Jessie who isn't afraid to tell him what's what like she does. I don't like the idea of Rick and Michonne. I think they make great friends and confidants but I hope it doesn't lead to anything more. I'm really hoping Michonne gets together with Morgan - they already seem to be developing a bit of chemistry of his so-called missing peanut butter protein bar....ha ha ha...
Never before...  even for the leading cast members.  An hour and a half for one person (is he that popular?) is just toooooo much.

Novelty is starting to wear off. Guess it has been for the last year. Basically turning into a soap opera with zombies. Still an interesting watch, but I am basically waiting for Season 2 of Mr. Robot and Better Call Saul. This is just "killing" time for now.

I'm reviewing the last episode of season 6 "Trouble is inside and outside the gate," playing off of the episode that saw the Ws get into the compound, just before this episode. I'm writing this review because we think that any humans in this position would be discussing ways to prevent further attacks and breakthroughs in the perimeter, and put on hold love stories and emotional problems. It's human nature to go into survival mode until the threat is dealt with. It is not human nature to want to have sex or discuss long term human relations when you think your life in danger. I know some of you will disagree with that, but it is true. There is plenty of time to have those interaction in this series, but not right on top of the after math of murderous criminals breaking easily through their perimeter and murdering them. That's a little hard to swallow.

It's interesting from a tactical point of view, and my friend and I both had this same problem with the entire series. We both have military background, and we understand the imperative nature of secure perimeters and tactically advantageous positioning. We were trained that way. This is a good episode to critique in that there is a bonified military person in their ranks, Abraham, but we don't even see him advising Rick on perimeter defenses. Let me tell you something. ANY military person trained in tactical defense will immediately be looking for perimeter defense possibilities upon this type of activity--you know, the zombies, bad people, etc. It's drilled into us. Yet, nothing so far. (One exception is that Rick did bring up the supports for the wall being a possible way into the compound.)

That said, tactical strategy is mostly common sense, except for the physics of trajectory flight. And then, a basic understanding of that can be gotten from simple experience suffices. For instance, if you have high ground, your projectiles have a greater distance than you opponents--you're firing downhill, while they must fire uphill. In a close situation, that isn't going to matter. But when using arrows or hand held projectiles, it means the difference between winning and losing. Think of it as dropping rocks down a mine shaft onto your enemy while he or she must throw them up to hit you. It is the exact same principle.

That's just one example of tactically advantageous positioning, but like I was saying, it becomes fairly common sensical if you are in such a situation where you experience it first hand.

So with that said, enter TWD.

So Rick is pretty good at understanding tactically advantageous positioning, and perhaps they will have a discussion on how to "harden" their position in the next episode. Perhaps they will not because we have seen the characters make huge tactical mistakes, commonsensical things you would not think people in their situation would make over and over again. Let's start and end with their current situation.

First, the fence was built wrong, and any architect would know that. The force is coming from outside, therefore you put the supports on the INSIDE. Can anyone see that? It's one of those common sense types things where force coming from one direction is met with resistance front the opposite. Think of it as if someone is pushing you backwards. You automatically extend one of your legs out and to your back, opposite side of where the force is coming. The same principle applies to any support.  Like I said, any architect would understand that. Pretty hard to understand how the writers could have an architect build something like that.

Rick noticed that in some degree. When he first got there, he said, which is also correct, that anyone wanting to get inside could simply climb the outside supports and jump the wall. For any one constructing a base, that would have been a top priority to fix, before any other construction was performed. But, they failed to do it and sure enough, they came over the top.

I would also like to say that a properly hardened position will require  three times the number of people to overcome it. That means if you are in a fortified position, say a castle, and it has been built properly, it will take your opponents three times the resources to defeat you, all things being equal. That means three times the personnel, three times the ammo, etc. So let's move on.

So now from the last episode we saw that there was a great concern by Carol that the Ws  would find the armory and use the guns on the towns good people. This concern is CORRECT! You NEVER want to leave ordinance lying around for others to use on you. Thus, priority number two, after the fence or at the same time, would be to build a secure armory for the ordinance and firearms. Yet, they haven't even discussed that yet. Currently, the ordinance is behind a household door and nothing else. Next.

The fence is good, and it might even stop a large tractor trailer from going through it. However, the entrance is weak and will not stop a large vehicle from plowing through. This is known by the residence because they discuss it referring to the character who shot out the driver and caused the truck to hit a stronger place in the fence. The solution is to use, for instance, seatrains or large tractor trailers (turned on their sides) to make a corridor heading up the entrance, one that requires at least two switch back turns, in order to slow any hostile from getting any speed.

Perimeter defense. The fence simply needs reinforcement from large vehicle attacks. We already know the people of the town are resourceful and have access to heavy equipment. It would be quite easy to round up the necessary trailers and or seatrains and put those around the outside of the fence. You would want to leave enough space between each trailer for personnel to move though, but only at strategic locations. Those are called "kill areas." They call them kill areas because they represent the place where it is easiest to get through the first perimeter. Of course, you would have your gunners already zeroed in on those locations, and when they come through, they are an easy target. You make it as hard as your situation allows for them to go right through the hardest aspect of the perimeter. Sure, they can hook up to the trailers and try to tow them off, but that takes lots of time and they are getting shot at the entire time. And that's what you are buying in a situation like this. It's a war of attrition. If you make to hard enough, your opponents will stop. You can also use heavy equipment to build up a dirt berm around the fence, making sure it is no too high, depending on how high the fence is. That was you can still fire down past the burn from the fence onto the enemy, making sure your berm gives them no cover at all. A six foot berm with a high angle of attack will stop just about any non tracked vehicle, until the attackers can dig out of it.  Again, as one builds these things, it becomes common sense about how to build them. You can also use sandbags about two feet from the fence, 4' high, 4' deep which absorb any impact, saving the fence.

Clear all vegetation, including trees, around the entire town for at least 100 yards. That makes it necessary for attackers to be in the open for 100 yards before they reach your perimeter. Easy kills.

Last, when constructing any position, you want a fall back area, which will also be fortified. It's also where your first line of tactical planning takes place, the field planners that plan how to defeat the attackers. And, you want a last fall back position where your higher ranking planners are, they can be outfitting in a tower with binoculars, in this show's instance, for spotting enemy movement, and then relayed to the other tactical position planners.

So in summary, the people in Rick's group should well know that priority one is:
(1) Front entry reinforcement.
(2) Wall reinforcement with kill pathways.
(3) Moving wall support beams to the INSIDE (geeze, really writers?).
(4) Hardened fall back positions inside of the wall.
(5) Hardened armory with very limited access (inside of a seatrain which has been barricaded from all but one entry point, with multiple pathway obstructions (locked steel doors, gunmen, check points).
(6) Having a treeless open area at least 100 yards all around the perimeter. That way any attackers must move over 100 years of open area.

I think most humans in this particular situation would be screaming about how to harden their position. That's because it is human instinct to go into survival mode, and part of that is reinforcing your position. This lack of planning has us cringing when we fail to see any of it. It's just not realistic with a law enforcement person and a military person in Ricks group.

'SPOILERS'
'Now' reveals how truly stuck in the mud this show really is.
The plot is ridiculous ! Perhaps the largest walker hoard in the history of this show is at the gates of the only known piece of civilization remaining on earth and the community members decide to wander off into their own little make believe worlds, baking cookies and getting drunk, while their leader decides to review the plans for next season's crops, ITS ABSURD !
I can only conclude that the current residents of the community are not its original inhabitants because there is no way this bunch of self pitied fools constructed the wall and built a sustainable infrastructure.
The dialog is atrocious ! Maggie's tunnel rant highlights the mush of disconnected sentences that form the script. Maggie doesn't even make sense when delivering a monologue, never mind when two or more characters interact. A perfect example is when the boy approaches Rick, who is on watch at the wall, to explain the incident between himself and Rick's son. Rick begins to leave, to check on his son, only to be dissuaded by the boy on the guise of showing him how to shoot a gun.
What's going on in Rick's mind ? It should already be dramatic enough that Rick struggles with the priorities of abandoning his watch on the wall in order to check on the welfare of his son, only to flippantly dismiss this struggle for the new highest priority of showing a kid how to use a gun. ITS RIDICULOUS !
The community has no intention of fortifying their defenses against the hoard and, even if they did, cannot effectively communicate with each other in order to put a plan in to action.
At this point I'm rooting for the hoard to knock down the wall and feast on the entire community.

I concur with everything Michael said- the show is NOT about the zombies.  Initially, I avoided watching the show because while channel flipping all I seemed to catch was scenes where people were being attacked.  That was until the scene where the group came upon Hershel's farm.  Being an animal lover, I had to watch and make sure the animals were kept safe and before that show was over I was hooked.  I have my own horse farm and while I was concerned for the animals being kept safe, I became invested in the group's safety and how they learned to work together to survive.  And, then of course, learning to deal with the living who were a danger to the group- like Shane and others.
going to happen next.  There was a time when I couldn't think about anything except the show, waiting with such great anticipation to the next episode to see what was going to happen next and how the group would persevere.  Watching characters like Daryl and Carol evolve has been amazing!  I miss Hershel, but am glad he was part of the group at least for a time.  I also miss Beth and her beautiful voice and her wonderful innocence to life.

It makes me think about the future of our own world and the things we do as a society to destroy it.  I think some people are afraid to think that at the rate we are going, we are headed in this direction.  Maybe there will be nuclear war or maybe due to chemical warfare or something similar we will all be forced off the grid and learn how to survive by going back to the basics.  This show makes one think, "what if..."  What would each of do to survive?

The Walking Dead has to be viewed from the beginning.  It can be pure zoned-out entertainment.  If you look somewhat deeper, you can see the stereotyped personalities, how they are portrayed dealing with psychosocial and other stresses, as well as how humans hypothetically form social groups (civilization) under constant threat.  In this case the constant threat is the Zombies.  However, recall that it was not that many years ago when death of a mother during childbirth was not uncommon, and usually the baby's life was saved first (e.g. caesarian).

If you can turn off all of the analytics for a while, I would call this a guilty pleasure, as some people refer to the occasional chocolate bar.

If you have to wonder how they make the zombies, you're missing the fun part of it.

I was absolutely a Die Hard fan in Seasons 1 and 2.  Season 3 was a struggle to get through. Season 4 somewhat redeeming.  Season 5 was up and down.  Nonetheless, I eagerly maintained that the old Walking Dead filmic fascination would reappear in the very next episode.  Practically held my breath in wait for each season's first episode, the mid-season, and the grand finale.  It had to get better, I knew it would, it had to.  But #@!#?  Im not even sure what I'm watching anymore -- a big guy showing a little guy how to wield a Zen stick, some cooking tips, a naughty goat, that was the entire show!  Meanwhile, zombies popped up like groundhogs in a pop up box.  Thats all I got out of the 11/1/15 episode.  The producers and directors of The Walking Dead are full of themselves.  In the first couple of seasons they emancipated the zombie stereotype, building it into something sublimely artful -- now they are taking just as much liberty in ruining it.  Maybe the success was too much for them.  Well, I never thought it was about them anyway -- Id LOVE to see the producers and directors get eaten by zombies -- please someone mutiny the set, seize the script and write that scene into it.  Maybe then we will see on The Walking Dead what weve been waiting for.  Writers rock  and so do all of the many people it takes to produce a TV show -- but when you take away a main character, the actor, that youve put so much into building  then it becomes boring and hopeless.  If those main characters are truly unessential, and easily replaced, then most certainly the rest of the film crew from the very top to bottom can be easily replaced too, oh yes.  There IS nothing more important in a show than the actor that can turn the switch on from typewritten script to film.  When youve got a story line thats going nowhere, no new plots, nothing new weve found out about the post-apocalyptic world in a seemingly very long time, all youve got is those characters to hang on to.  As of this writing, all The Walking Dead is about is getting rid of the characters we cant live without, ensuring that all the show has left is dead ends.

This is a review of Episode 10. Not to be a nit picker or anything....this show rocked and I LOVE the new character "Jesus". OK...first when Carl and Little Ass Kicker are sitting on the porch he's pointing out stars. I've found in this show that the quiet moments have meaning and come back around to save someone's life. Carl tells Judith "...see, that's the North Star, it's lives in the Little Dipper and it's red, you follow it and you'll always find your way home". The North Star does not live in the Little Dipper. You trace the two stars that form the outer edge of the Big Dipper up, and that is the North Star. The North Star is not red. The North Star is Polaris, a yellow super giant star that shines with the brightness of 2500 of our Sun. It sits at true celestial North and all other stars in our sky wheel around it. So Carl, get it right if you're trying to help out your sister. I know, she's a baby...but still, it's the Walking Dead and her name is "Little Ass Kicker". Ok...Second, when Rick and Daryl are coming back with "new character, Jesus" I noticed a new sign on their gate. It said: "Welcome to the Alexandria Safe Zone. Mercy for the Lost- Vengeance for the Plunderers.".......what the heck does Vengeance for the Plunderers, mean? Why would people that plunder need vengeance, and why would the folks in Alexandria have any thing to do with that? Did the village idiot write the sign? Shouldn't it read; "Vengeance for the Plundered?" Someone help me out here? Other than these two solids points, this show ROCKS BALLS!!! Best Show EVER. Maybe even better than Vikings?? Oops. I sincerely hope that this show goes on for several more seasons.  It is that good!

This season has a split personality. The first half really worked for me, but the second half just made me frustrated and angry at the writers. It felt like two different seasons, which in-and-of itself isn't a problem, but it left me feeling like I really didn't need to watch season 6.

I just purchased the Season 6 season pass, as this will allow me to watch all the episode online this season AND to re-watch them whenever I need zombie gore mixed with the Big Questions in life, such as: Why go on? What's worth living for? What's the point of all of this? And so on.

But the thing is that this is the third Walking Dead season pass I've purchased on Amazon. So this leads me to wonder: Why on Earth can't we buy multi-season passes? And why don't my previous season passes in any way count toward future season passes? I'm not saying I don't like The Walking Dead, because I think it's the best show on TV in a long time, I'm just saying that this Amazon season pass business needs to be worked out and improved.

This is not an unfavorable review and there are no Season 6 spoilers.  I binged watched every Season episode without commercials and I still experience TWD as an OK thriller drama.  These are my ten reasons for this rating:

 1. It is illogical.  The Zombies herds can be lured, trapped and killed by fire. Yet, the surviving humans can not seem to develop ways to exterminate Zombies out of one small town.

2.  The group goes in and out of the city and the one place that I would think they would select, (Grady Hospital) due to the security is the one place they leave. For months, they complained about lack of medical care, food, water, guns and then they leave the hospital which has all of these things for the misery of the woods.

3. It is very, very difficult to grab a tame or wild horse with your bare hands. Nonetheless a group of Zombies with rotting flesh can easily grab, pull down and manage of tear open a living horse in less than 30 seconds.  Some writer apparently hates horses, because Zombies have killed at least four horses.

4. A rotting human body has an unreal, disgusting funk, it is the kind of odor the creates immediate nausea.  Nonetheless, no one can smell Zombies, they have to listen for them.  Zombies make noise, except when they are trying to attack from behind.  So it is very easy to get a surprise attacked and eaten.

5. Every time they went out on a run, no one ever thought about, getting some barb wire fencing, so that at least the Zombies could not walk on the farm and eat people and animals.

6. Baby Judith always looks fat and healthy.  Yet for days she has not had anything to eat except forest food. How is her diaper being cleaned? How are the women cleaning themselves after a period?  They all seem to be very comfortable wearing skin tight jeans in hot weather walking along in the Georgia woods, full of all kinds of insects.  Listen up writer, in hot weather your garments are loose fit pants, the looser the better.

7. The writers try to make sense out of nonsense.  In the prison, Rick wanted to kill all the inmates, immediately, but then changed his mind due to their pleadings.  Out of the prison, Rick did not want to kill the Governor, and never attempted to kill him, even though he knew the man was a totally crazy psycho.

8. The Governor is smarter than Rick, because he trapped wandering Zombies.  A trapped Zombie is easier to kill than a walking Zombie. The Governor managed for months a very safe community and never once had any problems with keeping a woman. Rick was basically under Hershel's authority and killed a best friend that wanted his wife.

9. The stupidity of Beth thinking a small bandage scissor would penetrate a bullet proof vest.  Beth, walk to Rick, take his gun and shoot the woman in the head at a safe distance.

10. The Zombies are rotting corpses, they are not really Zombies which are alive but unable to communicate.  So where are the vultures and ravens, eating the Zombies?  Where are all the insect flesh eaters?  Every Zombie encountered should be eaten down to the bones or covered head to toe with the bugs that feed off dead flesh.

Finally,there is no such creature as a virus that is 100% lethal, someone in these episodes should be immune to the Zombie virus.

The Walking Dead is a comic book, graphic novel story.  It is not a classic horror fiction, such as Dracula, Frankenstein, etc, etc.  The characters do everything against surviving, because no one can give up their craziness long enough.  No one has any faith in any religion.  In fact, the episodes are basically religious free, except for a rare ten second view of a Biblical text.  Yet, they all believe that human effort will lead them to a safe place.  Trying to figure out which character survives or dies represents TWD's foundation thrill quest.  TWD is very similar to viewing a slasher film and guessing which person or persons will end up making it to the end of the movie  Except TWD has millions of monsters.  It's an average thriller soap opera drama with wonderful special effects and makeup.  It is not the best TV show and it is not the worst either.

Let us talk about Walking SHOES for a moment.  Throughout the seasons, I've never spotted a shoe-less or barefoot  Walker. The thousands of potential footwear shoppers are flitting about the countryside wearing the STURDIEST footwear ever cobbled together by a cobbler!. Apparently, our Walker friends are keeping an eye ( or two ) out for any shoe stores they may wander by, in order to take a breather to  roam the aisles for an appropriate pair of shoes suitable for the climate, the terrain, distance, urgency,...etc.. As usual, absolutely wonderful. Real to life in the sense of the decisions and how people react in difficult times of danger and sorrow. This show is not about Zombies, it is about a horrible living  condition and how you survive  and keep your humanity alive within it. It deals with personal ethics, moral codes and how that affects the greater good depending on your choices. I love the characters and frankly how season after season it does NOT lose the ability to surprise us the fans. Story writing and development is excellent in a category all by itself. The people who write, produce, act and collaborate in The Walking Dead really work well together and I mean really, really, really give it their best. I get a sense from what I have observed that these folks communicate  a whole lot with each other, listen a lot to one another and have a great agreement together on the final product. That is what has made them the number # 1 show on the planet. That is what their success is based on!

Season 6 seems a little bit faster than season 5, but not that much. The creators of The Walking Dead continue to annoy us with slow moving scenes, long stares, characters asking questions and taking their sweet time to answer. Episode 1 was extremely disjointed, going back and forth between the present and the past. Then episode 2 instead of continuing with the cliffhanger, gave us an entirely different story. I'm not sure what they're doing, maybe they're trying to keep us surprised?

Why can't they stick to this simple formula? Killing Zombies + Interesting Situations = Great Programming

Why don't they explore character's motivations? On episode 2 a bunch of barbarians are invading that beautiful residential community with homes from the $800s. Why are they invading? Why do they have a "W" in their foreheads? We don't know! Will we know in the future? And why are they killing some while capturing others?

And what's the deal with the sheriff's son having that horrible haircut? Those bangs are hideous! I realize it's the apocalypse, but come on! Foreheads shouldn't be hidden!

The zombie-gore continues to escalate, with the special effects becoming more and more elaborate, grotesque, and revolting; regardless of the attractions of the more intellectual stimulation provided, if you can't handle that, stay away. I agree completely about this not being a zombie show. In fact, I think as every season goes by it becomes less and less of a zombie show. Yes, they are there and we always have a few gory scenes with them. But by far that action that consumes us is the human to human tension as the remaining people struggle NOT to become zombies themselves.

It admittedly took me a bit to sink back into the show as this season began. The constant flashbacks of the first episode were not pulling me in but all of those zombies in the valley certainly did visually. However, with this last episode, which was dominated by Carol, I really was fully back into it. Carol is fast becoming a very favorite character. She is very clear about her perspective of what they are facing both now and for the future. She faces that bleak prospect with unrelenting fortitude. Her character was on display all of this latest episode on Oct 18th. This episode also brought to the forefront the human vs. human battle which is ongoing, each faction seeking to escape the zombie end for itself. The people they fight this time have let go of any pretense of civilization. They might as well be marauding beasts. Prior villains, like The Governor, at least had the veneer of civilization about them.

Whether I like it or not is almost beside the point though. This is referred to as AMC's ratings juggernaut. Neither "Mad Men" nor "Breaking Bad" ever achieved that status, excellent as they were. But here the viewing audience has clearly spoken, with both thumbs up.

I've loved every minute of TWD since season 1 episode 1. Started watching mainly because of Frank Darabont (Shawshank Redemption) and Gale Anne Hurd (too much cred to go into). For those who haven't followed this series, let me just say it's really not about zombies but instead what it means to be alive and human. This is a heavily character-driven drama with 'the dead' as antagonists. The characters are very sympathetic and the story is so engrossing, you'll forget your watching a television show. I'd go so far as to say it's better than 75% of the feature films I've seen in the last 5 years. However, with season 6 the production values, script, characters and story have been taken to a whole new level. It's a good season for new viewers because there is a kind of restart or full circle in the first episode. If this was just about the zombies and gore factor, it wouldn't have lasted 6 seasons and been one of the highest rated cable shows in history--just sayin'. Can't wait to see where TWD goes from here!

Everyone is wondering how far Rick is going to go, and whether he will actually become a tyrant.  Seeing that potential lurking under the surface gives you all the more reason to really root for him...and that's what is fascinating about his character: I am not sure if I am rooting for him to be the Hero we used to have, are become the new ruthless Rick that keeps his friends in check and his enemies in checkmate.  All I know for sure is that I can't wait to watch more, and if the first episode is any indication, TWD is definitely not done with give us thrills.

The Walking Dead has finally returned for a new season (thank God!), and so far it looks like more amazing shows are headed our way. The season opener presents an enormous threat to the safety of Alexadria with the show's most humongous zombie horde so far. The discovery of a quarry full of trapped walkers makes the necessity of Rick's group in Alexandria evident to everyone, and the town's sheltered residents must now go into training mode to learn how to fend them off. This allows for several new dynamics to emerge. Rick's people must now become teachers, and that process allows for some amends to be made, and the opportunity for some Alexandrians to redeem themselves. However, it creates tension elsewhere as Rick realizes the chance to thin the town's herd a bit and weed out a few of the weaker residents who could pose a threat. Also, Morgan finally becomes a regular after popping up sporadically over the first five seasons. As expected, he and Rick don't strike an immediately harmonious chord despite their past loyalty to one another. Rick has become far more cold, while Morgan appears to have somehow found a greater sense of humanity. Season 6 has many avenues to explore as Alexandria attempts to fortify itself, Rick and Morgan look to resolve their differences, the Wolves draw nearer, and someone inside the town appears to have gone traitor (my bet is on that massive douche Gabriel). With the show's creative potential as promising as ever, The Walking Dead should not lose any of its momentum during this season.

(The Gabriel comment referred to my belief that he set off the horn at the end of Episode 1. I was wrong, which in no way reduces the massiveness of Gabriel's douchery.)

Here we are again, at the start of a brand new season. We all know the emotional turmoil that this season will most likely bring, but at the same time, it's going incredibly entertaining. My only wish is that they don't kill off any of the original cast members. They all feel so essential to the show at this point, that even losing one cast member might throw the show off. In a way, I guess that's what makes this show so great. The fear that any character (except Rick obviously) could die will always keep you in suspense.

I love the usage of flashbacks in this first episode. They blended the past and present so well together -- it was a really great way of story-telling. It's very clear at this point who the top dog is. Rick is trying very hard to make this his final home. He's got so much faith in this new community and he's going to protect it no matter what, even if he has to knock a few heads together.

The introduction of the Morgan, the staff wielding weapons expert that we know and love from the very first season is a very good addition to the team. He brings a calm, collective, and reasonable side and will definitely be a crucial part of the team. I think at this point, he might be the only person who can make Rick see who he's become.
