TWD Season 6 Episode 1 Review: No Spoilers
The pacing on this one was just....incredible. It never moved too slow or went too fast for the viewer. Everything just "clicked" exactly right. The character development also moved along just as it should--a hint here and there, a mere facial expression or one sentence and it opened whole new possibilities for Characters their relationships and future development. Understated Perfection. There were surprises this episode, but Not the ones you expected. That's right, I said it. The acting was impeccable by all parties, but this time I was really impressed with the supporting cast, especially the major and the main "enemy" of this show--just from his facial expressions alone, you Knew Him. Moving from black and white to color was PERFECT! In fact, the Flashbacks were the best I've ever seen in Any television show or movie. They moved together just right, like a deck of cards being shuffled so smoothly by a master dealer, the sound is like a whisper of music. They never felt jarring or silly but dealt out past and present as a gasp inducing royal Flush.
The Direction, the editing, the zombies make-up, costumes, sheer size of the cast, huge kudos to whomever was managing THAT behind the scenes.....
Everything in This Episode just went exactly as it should. I think when they reviewed it before airing it, people should have stood up and given everyone involved a standing ovation and cried in joy.
The ending...gut wrenching suspense! Excellently done!
6 Stars (an extra star for the flashbacks alone!)

I think we need to recap some Season 5 last episodes a bit:

A guy is such a coward and so plain evil he gets one of your friends killed, then he ambushes you in the woods trying to kill you or get you fed to the walkers, your response is:

A -  Kick his butt and then put a bullet in his brain to end any future threat.
B -  Win the fight and then tie him to a tree and listen to the walkers have lunch as you walk back to safety.
C -  Win the fight, tend his wounds a bit (that you just gave him while trying to save your life), then while beaten and wounded, you carry him on your back to safety.

OK, Answer time.

If you picked A, you are a practical and logical human with strong survival skills
If you picked B, your fighting skills are only exceeded by your overall badassery
If you picked C, you are Glenn and your TSTL card (Too Stupid To Live) is in the mail and we wonder if you are going to be on the menu for some walker in the near future.

OK folks, yes it's zombies, but it is NOT about zombies. Yes, I said it, ZOMBIES, because that is what most of the non-waking public of non-zombie watchers calls them. The show is about the people surviving in a world that has been turned on its ear. How do you start the world all over again? It is a form of caveman days revisited with cars that run on scrounged gasoline, and your food from old canned goods or a lucky-find fruit tree. Your mind is constantly thinking of how to solve their problems for them. Much of the day to day minutiae is not really covered or the show would cover nothing but where they found a meal for a day. As you wind your way through all the seasons of the Walking Dead the battle for survival on a 24 hour basis runs the gamut of finding shelter, finding food, fighting walkers, fighting other survivors, finding a cure, finding other civilized survivors, finding survivors that aren't lying about being civilized, and basically trying find some kind of a normal life among the chaos.

The Walking Dead is the number one show for a reason, it delivers on every level of entertainment. There are no scenes of happy people purchasing new cars and going on luxury hotel excursions. Not sleeping on the ground is a triumph for the cast of the Dead. It is bloody and gory at times, and touching and gripping maybe minutes later. The cast is made up of veritable no-names who are now famous worldwide.  Watch it to follow the people and their desperate existence, and not for the reanimated DEAD. The DEAD are merely obstacles in a rocky road of survival that features far more nasty pitfalls than the lumbering masses.

The two halves of The Walking Dead's fifth season are quite distinct from one another as AMC makes effective use of the two-part season strategy. The first half is pure brutality, with Rick's group facing off in back-to-back wars against Terminus and the Atlanta Hospital. First, they have to fight their way out of Terminus like rats in a trap, teaching the renegades running the place that they were indeed f'ing with the wrong people. Then, after a harrowing escape, they go against the hospital and the Atlanta police. Unfortunately, they don't make it out of this showdown unscathed, setting up their reunion and leaving them to pick up the pieces. Back on the road, the second half of the season hits just as hard, with more shocking character deaths keeping the audience constantly on its toes. The group eventually makes it to another supposed safe haven, the town of Alexandria. The loss of humanity they've experienced after years of survival is never more apparent than when it's contrasted with the relative civilization of Alexandria. They each struggle individually to adapt, with Carol proving to be the most effective, cold, and calculating survivalist in the group. As they find their places within the town, it's quite the sight to behold Rick as an active police officer again, something I never thought would be possible after seeing the complete breakdown of society in the first four seasons. But it's still not enough to bring Rick back to his former self, as the season ends with him advocating public executions in the town. As long-lost Morgan finds his way to Alexandria at season's end, we're left to wonder how it will all play out in Season 6. Like most of the country, I can't wait to see The Walking Dead return for more apocalyptic insanity.

Its the WALKING DEAD Mannnn!  You would think that says it all.. BUT nope!  The the scope of the interactions with the "family" of our dearly loved regulars is astounding.  This truly shows the epic struggle of man vs everyone and everything as our group moves into each trial set before them.  I have now watched ep 1 and 2 of season 6.  OMG.. yes i said it.. and I mean it.  I have watched this series from the pilot.. and I re watch it from pilot to the end of the last aired season before the new season starts.. SO i have watched TWD more than a few times..
I get irritated when i hear the "I hate Zombies" stuff.. if you haven't watched it, you are really clueless as to what TRUE television is about.  Good verses Evil?.. No.  Survival.. What is a normal person willing to do to survive an inescapable catastrophe..  The disarming of ones inner moral fiber, to degenerate to pure animalistic behavior...  to hold on to the life values you had.. Mentally, where do you go to survive?
There is way more to this than not dying.  At least more than physical death.  The loss of emotion,  feeling or caring... You can die inside without ever being bit.  All in all.. this is a survival drama with some zombies added in.. Icing on the cake.

Late to the game Walking Dead junkies here.  My wife and I had been talking about starting a new series.  We hate to start a new one until it is up and running because sure enough, a few episodes in and it seems they get dropped leaving you wondering who killed Laura Palmer.  Well with five seasons we felt that if we liked it we had a good six months of entertainment ahead of us... that was three weeks ago.

We have Netflix and Seasons 1-4 are all free on Netflix so I assumed we were good.  But about 18 days and four seasons later (no lie) my wife demanded, I won't say she would shiv me in the brain if I didn't, but she certainly forcefully demanded that I immediately order the next season.  I did, and four days later it was consumed.  I am assuming if you are looking at Season 5 you already know what to expect.  But for me, for us, what to expect and the Walking Dead are two different things.  Every other promising show (Lost for example) may have a great first or second season but after that we just sit and wait for the end of season cliff hanger, will the one character survive.  No spoiler here... you just never know.  People are people and when you think you know the way they are they are living in a zombie apocalypse so they just might wind up a little different than you think.  Otherwise normal people may be pushed past a limit and otherwise passive people may step up.  In other words, if you missed Season 5 and are awaiting Season Six do not hesitate, pull the trigger (or the bow string), for the price of a couple of IMAX tickets you get an entire season.  Well, well worth it.

The Walking Dead: The Complete Fifth Season begins with the outstanding episode, No Sanctuary, one of the most action-packed, bloodiest of the series. Season 4 concluded with Rick (Andrew Lincoln) and the group outnumbered, outgunned, and trapped in a shipping container at the mercy of Gareth and his band of cannibals. The outlook was bleak.

Apart from season opening and finale episodes, the shows too often lapse into long, talky sequences that slow the pace and kill suspense. The show is about humans defending themselves from becoming zombie meals, but we have back stories, conflicts, and assorted treks to supposedly safe locations.

Special effects are the best on television, easily ranking with what you can see in Hollywood features. The producers keep coming up with new and ghastly images, and I suppose thats what keeps viewers coming back. Its tough sustaining any series for more than three seasons, especially one whose goal is shocking viewers. Even deaths of key characters have become predictable, occurring for the most part in season finales. Still, despite these shortcomings, The Walking Dead is a gruesomely effective horror series.

Bonus extras on the Blu-ray release include several behind-the-scenes featurettes, audio commentaries, and deleted scenes.

I simply cannot say enough good things about THE WALKING DEAD.  I have had the privilege to review each season as it has been released on DVD/Blu-ray, and each time I laud the show for what it is and what it represents.  But my reviews do not do the show justice.  It is that good.  I am in my forties, and I cannot think of another show in all my years of TV watching that has been this impressive.  Season 5 continues this tradition of excellence, and I am extremely proud to state it is my favorite season thus far.

I think Ive said this before, but one of the most impressive aspects about this show is how NO character is safe.  The writers have no qualms about killing anyone off, regardless of how major or minor their role in the storyline is.  Just knowing that your favorite character could die during any episode ratchets the tension up exponentially.

As with each previous season, THE WALKING DEAD is shot well and looks like a movie.  The production value is way high, which allows for deeper immersion into each episode.  I daresay this is the best looking show on television.

The acting is again superb, with Andrew Lincoln headlining an amazing cast.  The regulars (who have survived previous seasons) are once again present as well, including Norman Reedus as Daryl, Steven Yeun as Glenn, Lauren Cohan as Maggie, Chandler Riggs as Carl, Danai Gurira as Michonne, and Melissa McBride as Carol.  Newcomers to this season include Seth Gilliam, who portrays the downtrodden priest, Gabriel; Josh McDermitt, who plays scientist Dr. Eugene Porter; and Christian Serratos, who shines as Rosita Espinosa, Abrahams girlfriend, just name a few.

The special effects in season 5 of THE WALKING DEAD are once again stupendous.  They rival even the best movies that are being made today.  I particularly like how the zombies appear more and more decomposed as the show progresses.  This is a testament to the respect the production team gives the audience; they know we (as a whole) will expect rot to ensue as time passes.

THE WALKING DEAD season 5 is another huge win for me, and I recommend it whole-heartedly.  If you have never watched the show, do yourself a favor and give it a look.  If you're up-to-date on the television episodes, snatch this season 5 set up immediately to add to your collection.  The Blu-ray version has an excellent HD picture and sound, and some nice Special Features as well, including:

* Featurettes, such as Inside the Walking Dead; The Making of The Walking Dead; The Making of Alexandria; Beths Journey; Bobs Journey, etc.
* Audio Commentaries
* Deleted Scenes

and more.  Snag your copy today!

As I admitted when I reviewed the first four seasons of THE WALKING DEAD, with certain exceptions, I am not a fan of horror movies or television series.

I am even less a fan of the zombie movie.  Frankly, I think they are silly.

On the other hand, I love a well-written, intelligent scripteven if it is in the horror genre.  Good writing is good writing, no matter where you find it.

THE WALKING DEAD may have been adapted from a series of graphic novels by Robert Kirkman, and there are plenty of zombies walking around and feasting in the sixteen-episode fifth season, but these decaying creatures continue to take a back seat to the compelling human dramas that are played out between the survivors.

Because we, as an audience, come to care about these multi-dimensional characters, many who do not survive the season, when the zombies (aka: walkers) do attack they are anything but silly.  They are truly frightening.

Again, viewers who enjoy blood, guts and gore will not be disappointed, but unlike most zombie movies, thats not what this series is about.  In THE WALKING DEAD, story and character trump visceral delights.

As with my previous reviews, I am not going to give specific plot details, except to say that this season begins with the survivors escaping their railroad car captivity at Terminus, and then destroying the refuge.  As the season progresses, Andrew Lincolns character becomes much darker, and there are suspenseful story arcs set in a remote country church, a hospital in Atlanta and, finally, a fortified community in Alexandria, VA.

All of the performances in the show continue to be superb, as are the Georgia-filmed series visual effects, make-up and other elements.  Tovah Feldshuh, Christine Woods and Seth Gilliam appear this season in roles that makes one wonder who their characters really are, and Lennie James also returns.  This is, indeed, a first-rate production.

My chief concern, once again, about the programs future is: How long can the creators successfully continue the basic premise without resolving it?  Although Season Five ends with a powerful climax, it does, at times seem repetitive.  Indeed, how many ways are there to kill a zombie?

Hopefully, the producers will not allow this excellent series to overstay its welcome.

The five-disc Blu-ray from Anchor Bay Entertainment includes a full disc of extras, audio commentaries for many episodes, Behind the Scenes featurettes, and deleted scenes.  My one mayor complaint about the set is that there are no recaps at the start of each episode, which often makes it difficult to recall who certain character are if you haven't seen them for several episodes or, as in the case of Lennie James since Season 3.

 Michael B. Druxman

Too bad the Amazon ratings are skewed with negatives from the "online" viewing model, as opposed to the content and quality of the show itself :(

In any event, having gone back and watched everything right from Episode 1 is very rewarding, good advice and I'm glad I did it.
FYI, watching from disks, with the continuity of moving seamlessly from one episode to the next, creates a great "mood" and adds immeasurably to the enjoyment of the experience. The series almost plays like a good movie that just keeps going. And, this is a very good thing :)

The most recent season of the WD really fell flat for me. For all of the strong ratings and successes I would imagine the budget for the show has increased since previous seasons. However this season felt like the budget took a step backwards, and the directing wasn't on par with previous seasons. Of course the drama shifted mightily, and I understand why, but at the core of the show's success for me has always been an unflappable faith in Rick, and rooting for him to survive and protect those around him. Once you start posing questions at the heart of Rick, you jeopardize the formula for success with this show.  And as a friend of mine says "angry Rick is the best Rick."
I will stay with the WD until it's final episode whenever that is, so this season is necessary in totality. However, I'm hoping for an uptick in the season to come next.

Man, what can you say! I love the diversity of episodes this season. Some episodes to drive the story forward, some to explore our characters in depth, some episodes shot more artistically, and some more viscerally. I love that women and people of color are treated like important, fully conceived characters on this show. I love that 3 women can share a combat scene together without being treated like girls in distress. I love how this season explored the psychology and morality our favorite characters and the individuals populating the apocalypse remains of America.

The gore and death porn can go a little too far but, what can I say that others have not said elsewhere better than I? I'm just continually impressed. With the maturity with which the show is handled, the story moves forward, and how the characters grow and change. Bravo.

After finally binge watching this season I am definitely looking forward to the challenges foreshadowed in the next season.

Felt I should leave a review myself as there are so many negative one-star reviews all despairing over the high "initial" price point of this set. I feel like it's the same batch of people who do this every year; not realizing the prices drop before a show releases every single time. So please, do not let the high price scare you. If if does not drop before release, cancel your order and wait for the eventual sale. The show-makers cannot steal someone's money if it's voluntarily given. No one is being forced to buy anything.

Pre-ordered this set as soon as it became available. My current review is based on the quality of the season as seen of TV. I will update later when I get the actual product in the mail on release day. For what it's worth, I feel like this season is the best one since season two. It had tremendous acting all around and the plot was very engaging. I get a feeling that next season will be the best yet. As always, the plot is somewhat divided into two parts because of the break between November and February, but I'd rather get more bang for my buck as compared to the offerings of shows with fewer episodes than what is wanted or warranted (I'm looking at you Game of Thrones).

Also as normal is the higher quality of episodes at those certain spots in the season. For people like me who enjoy the slower, character building episodes however this is not an issue. It's almost guaranteed that if you've watched and enjoyed the prior seasons, you will enjoy this one. Don't hesitate to buy unless you're waiting for Black Friday like prices. You won't regret purchasing this season.

The fifth season of the walking dead has reinvigorated my love of this show. Season four had some really weak moments on the long road to Terminus and I believe the writers really stepped up their game for this one. There is a true sense of dread, loneliness, savagery and humanity painted this season.

There is a noticeable change in cinematography for the better, things feel grittier whilst at the same time real (truer) and brilliant - the last few episodes have some scenes that almost feel artsy like they were trying out some new things.

I'd highly recommend buying the whole season so you can sit back and have a good weekend of it.

Five seasons in and these idiots still can't clear a house. Let's all talk about our feelings in the middle of a fire fight. Zombies are attracted to noise so let's find the loudest most unreliable piece of s*** bike and ride it up and down and up and down and up and down the road announcing to God, baby Jesus and every zombie in a ten mile radius our exact location. Rick, a local law enforcement officer is completely ignorant as to the topology of his own county. None of them have any clue that there are fruit and nut trees everywhere. Not a Kevlar vest to be found. Automatic weapons???? No way, let's use a sword. I can top that with my crossbow. Let's top it by stabbing the zombies in the head with pocket knives. Let's go wonder through the woods unarmed because it's perfectly safe, that's where all the teens go to make out because there's not one room in the whole gated community where you can get a little privacy. Let's all make lots and lots and lots of noise every single scene all the time day and night no matter what the danger because we have to express how we are FEELING!!!. AR?,AK? Nah....I'm gonna use this here hammer. If they all fell off the short bus on the way the Chuck E Cheese in the very beginning, I would not only understand, but also sympathize and maybe even enjoy watching this band of merry glue sniffers as they lay starving in peach orchards as herds of zombies endlessly zero in on the noise from that oil leaking couch that Darryl rides. Not a Honda or Kawasaki to be found in the lower 48, no sir. How about a couple of nice quiet bicycles????? How dare you!?!?! You know what else they don't have in the south??? Fish!!!! No one fish or fishing rod or harpoon or lake or stream.... Nothing!! So let's recap..there are NO automatic weapons, fruit trees, nut trees, lakes, streams, ponds, fish, fishing rods, Kevlar vests, Honda motorcycles, maps, farms, wild game, bicycles, boats, riot gear, bullets, rope, pad locks, binoculars, compasses, or even pencils and paper for making notes on how to avoid zombies in the great state of Georgia.....yes that make perfect sense. It's all clear to me now.

Season Five begins with one of the most exciting and triumphant episodes they've ever aired (No Sanctuary). It's my favorite in the entire series. Though I believe most people would agree about that rock 'em sock 'em episode, there's a lot of divergence in opinion about the rest of this season. Critics loved it and applauded it's development of the characters and its ability to keep up with a number of separate strands., Others found the middle dragged with too much given over to the trapped situation of a character who had been fairly minor until now. Others were bummed by the down and desperate tone of Episode 10 (Them), though I found that a really truthful portrayal of just how grim a life on the road would be. It can't all be heroics and zombie killings. The second half of the season gradually introduces a whole new scene and many new characters and will obviously pay off next season. As usual there is a powerful season finale. Definitely worth seeing. Accept it for what it is, not just a fantasy of what someone would rather have it be.

WORTH SEEING TWICE. I'm glad I got these from Amazon (as HD streaming) because it allows me to see each episode more than once. I just finished watching the whole series to the end of ssn. 5 and it was well worth it. The first time around you'e so caught up in the plot, the tension, the wondering if a character is going to be killed by the zombies, that you miss a lot. Seeing it all a second time allowed me to pick up on many small details I missed the first time as well as many nuances of the characters. Also, it's much better without blocks of ads if you caught it first on AMC. I really highly recommend owning the whole series.

The story-line is suspenseful and full of action. I admit the Walking Dead characters are a little gory but compliment the acting. You get used to the head squashing after a while, and it passes without much thought later in the series. Overall, I rate it a five-star series. I have watched the entire five seasons, and I can hardly wait for season six to start in October 2015. B. Warden

Did the writers change for this season?  I don't follow that much but something was missing this season.  At first I thought the season was going to be interesting.  I understand that the group has to settle down somewhere and you can't just do the group fights bad guy all the time.  That is why I started watching this and have watched for 5 seasons.  I loved the character development and the stories between the characters but this season was very lacking in that development.  I understand that Rick could go bonkers and start becoming the bad guy but that just wasn't developed well enough to be believable.  And then all of a sudden he is NOT the bad guy and becomes the hallowed leader again?  Nahhhh....it didn't work.  And Carol's personality has just gone off the rails with no real sense of understanding about that.  I guess there is an assumption that you have been watching all the episodes but that is taking the audience for granted.  Don't take us for granted or we won't come back to watch the next seasons.

Walking Dead's Season 5 may, to some, be the best ever.  However, to this viewer it's the beginning of the great shark jump.  The entire season seemed to be a hodge-podge of ideas.  Who's right?  Why is Rick always in charge?  Doesn't it just annoy you the way he always leans in when he's going to talk?  This season may have been produced the way it was because the actors are likely charging more per episode than ever before.  Very few episodes had the core group together and when it did, the episode was mediocre at best.

Yes, I know, this is MY review and probably not the consensus of many.  But Walking Dead is now becoming, well, boring.

It took me a few years to watch this show because I do not like Zombie shows.  However, this show is so much more.  Brilliantly done and the messages that you get from each episode are deep and moving.  The cast couldn't be better and the way the relationships are built and enhanced with each season is wonderful.  The story line is intelligent and the way it is done is incredible.  When I started watching on Netflix, I watched the entire 4 seasons twice, then went to AMC for the 5th.  I still watch the re-runs every Wednesday.  I cannot wait till the next season.  I watch a lot of great shows on Netflix and tv, this one tops them all.  GREAT JOB to all the actors, producers and directors.  Also, the Talking Dead is really helpful to work through the episode and the losses (brilliant idea)!

What do I say about The Walking Dead. Well, I will start by saying that I don't watch much television, I am far to busy to get hooked into watching series. I usually watch documentaries, or the occasional H2 or Discovery type series. The last series on television that I really got into was 'Lost' on ABC. Well, The Walking Dead is and has been my one show since season 3, I discovered the pilot episode on netflix and proceeded to immerse myself in the full first two seasons. I have not stopped, it has become an obsession and I find myself looking for "Safe Zones" in my daily life. Yes this show is that good, that it carries over. I just can't stop thinking about it for days after each new episode. Amazing stuff, Great writing, Great acting (with the occasional southern accent flub by our British actors). I am always on the edge of my seat and champing at the bit for the next episode. Best show ever!

I no longer LIVE in America, so, I binge-watch my favorite shows in the summer as they are released for DVD/BD sale. ************************************************************************************************** This season was particularly interesting because of the RE-visit [via a dying man's ghost-haunting] of several former [dead] Characters from the show... you never know who is gonna DIE on this show! Such a thought provoking series about the demise of civilization, government, and society, but underneath the ties of family, friendship, and love, not to mention our human instinct to survive.

What would you do with $27.00 USD for entertainment? Would you go to AMC movies with a date? Would you go on a date for two at a restaurant? No. The right answer is to buy season 5 of the walking dead, which includes 16 full episodes, 10 hours of suspense, drama, and plot twists. $27 USD is the price of two Saturday night AMC movie tickets ($13.50 USD). Why bother going to the movies nowadays and deal with the hassle of waiting in line, crowded movie theaters, parking, lousy service, being at the mercy of others, and watching the same actors and actresses in all Hollywood movies. The Walking Dead represents mainstream USA; it represents us because we are the melting pot. We are the average joe, gay, different colors, straight, or whatever. In the end, we are the same and face the greatest threat of them all: zombies. The Walking Dead S5 is a smart buy.

This is the only bad line in the whole 65 minutes, and that is why it does not get six stars. the first episodes were just plain boring: full of flashbacks, everyone mopping around depressed and crying. It seems like the writers just ran out of ideas. The finale was not an earth-shattering, but it will suffice. I am not sure if I want to continue to watch. Maybe they should stop while they are ahead.

While the last episode maintained the integrity of the characters of the group, several of the preceding episodes felt like the actions of the main characters (primarily Rick) were not quite as believable as previous seasons. A few scenes seemed hastily put together during the last several episodes, but thankfully the ending seemed to tie things together in a way that the future of TWD can still be bright. My hope is that the writing for next season improves somewhat though (as this seems to be a true challenge for series that extend multiple seasons).

The season started off great with the first episode at Terminus, and in a slow pace sends the story of the group into a well crafted Season. Overall, I liked this season a lot, but did feel certain episodes caused me to feel disjointed and annoyed....but after you watch the whole season, you feel like you have read a well thought out book. For whatever reason, I think some of the casting is a little off, but probably intentional. I don't think that the Priest or Rick's new love interest was casted well....so I am hoping they both get killed off early next season. Not falling in love with the Alexandria community cast, but adjusting accordingly. If it wasn't for the season finale (plus Morgan coming back) wrapping everything up so well....I would have given this season 2 thumbs down, but kudos to the cast and producers for doing a great job.

This series builds on numerous current social parellels (helplessness, entitlement, gun control, diversity, capitol punishment, etc.) and often uses symbolism (the samurai sword that represents Michonne's survival strength/instinct, how the once-domesticated horse who lets his defences down when he comes in contact with Daryl but then subsequently fails to run away from the zombies represents the individuals in the group once they experience civilization at Alexandria).  You need to pay attention to catch all the references and keep up on the dialogue.  The graffic scenes are not as bad as one would think, maybe you just get used to them quickly as they are a recurrent thread to the series (you can only kill so many zombies before it becomes common place).  There are some anxiety producing scenes, but again, not terrifying.

It is pretty hard to write a review without spoilers, but I'll try. Season five is pretty bleak and everyone is in survival mode. Deaths of beloved characters, of course. It is important to look back at earlier seasons in order to really get the context of this one and the reasons for why the characters are behaving as they are and if they've become stronger or weaker or if they've just descended into a savagery that cannot be reversed. There are the occasional "moments of grace", as I call them, when they can laugh or enjoy something amazing. But it always returns to a brutal fight for survival. There are also cowards in this season that put in sharp relief how brave and honorable "our" group is, in their way. You will get angry and sad and hopeful and stunned and horrified and really run the gamut of emotions with our people through this season. Great tv, but like surviving a zombie apocalypse, not for the faint of heart.

I mean, how long can these poor jerks wander through the South, baking in the summer and freezing in the winter, before they get eaten up or the series ends? The Walking Dead is, in my opinion, one of the best shows on television.  Season 5 continues to show the transformation of all of our beloved characters--and some new ones--and how they cope with surviving what is essentially the end of the modern world as we know it.  This season really drives home the point that the real horror of this new world is less about the "walkers" and more about what is left of the human race.  Would HIGHLY recommend AFTER catching up on all the past episodes, this is not a show you pick up in the middle--this is a show in which you need to take the journey with the characters from the very beginning.

I've bought entire season 5 from Amazon, since I don't have cable tv & I was able to see the first 4 seasons on Netflix.  I care about the main characters on this series because they're surviving while preserving their grasp on what is good in humanity.  The world they live in is horrible and the situations they find themselves in are testing them in so many ways.  The show is like classical Greek drama and myth with heroes and villains and blood and horror and the plot of who is stronger and why.  Rick's group is stronger, vanquishing enemies like 'the governor' and Terminus because they care about each other and support each other.  They maintain a basic sense of right & wrong even though they fail sometimes.  My big question w/this series is - what is the cost of survival?

Carol to Rick (re Pete) "You're going to have to kill him."
That certainly is one conclusion.  And without Shane around to beat him into submission that may be the only conclusion from Carol's rather unique and practical perspective.

It is the Hobson's Choice though.  Because Pete is the doctor.  I'm unaware of any other doctors.  And a van load of wounded coming in.  Best answer?  Don't know...

What I do know is this - Alexandria is no paradise.  Even for the Alexandrians.  Deanna is as ruthless of Carol but I prefer Carol - at least she is not a politician!  And besides, I like cookies.

I guess anyone who watches walking dead for more than b movie zombie thrills should have seen this coming, right? I mean, season five was too good to be true. Great writing, great acting, great story... it was finally the walking dead we've all been waiting for, and it only took five years to figure it out. After the crew arrives in Alexandria, the stage is set for a slow and tense psychological drama with occasional intense zombie action for the gore hungry viewers who just can't go one episode without it, and episode 13 ends with a demented Rick apparently sympathizing with a zombie beyond their walls. Bravo, Gimple. Now, suddenly, all the good things they've done all season are put in a pile together and ceremoniously shat on. Character development? Only if you're going to kill them that episode! Is the character black? EVEN BETTER! We all know black characters MUST DIE on The Walking Dead (unless of course they have boobs. Has anyone noticed boobs keep you alive way more than anything else in the Zombie apocalypse?). By the way- did you think maybe we had something to worry about with this gun toting Tobin character? Naw. Why not make him, and every single other person in this outrageously stable community, COMPLETELY useless- like red shirts on Star Trek. Hey- remember that INCREDIBLE scene with Carol and the little boy Sam from last episode? I've got an idea. Let's make them close friends IMMEDIATELY AFTER THAT. Hey, remember how Deryl was real thankful for the bike parts Aiden offered him, and it was super touching? Instead of doing more interesting character development with that exchange, like showcasing CONVERSATIONS between them while they work on said bike, let's just say Deryl built his bike LITERALLY OVERNIGHT! FROM SCRATCH! Let's also say that Alexandria's two man recon crew are more petrified of walkers than Eugene, even though we JUST saw that they had one strung up in the woods to play with (and by the way, a two man recon crew... that's all they have? There are zero smoke and mirrors involved in this thing? The lady in charge has absolutely no ulterior motive or secret she's holding onto?). Literally nothing in this episode made sense, and Walking Dead has once again descended to the level of zombie soap opera. What hurts isn't that it happened, what hurts is that it KEEPS happening... the cosmic irony being that the new "twist" in this episode's finale is an abusive relationship that Rick (apparently) will have no choice but to just straight up murder a dude over (as if there is no other option to even consider in the mind of Carol), since I've personally been in a very similar abusive relationship with Walking Dead for YEARS. It always tells me it loves me, then it hits me, then I keep coming back for more (and here we are again). The sloppy writing is back in spades, with characters making decisions that largely make no sense, character development almost exclusively leading up to that character's death, and peripheral characters doing and saying things are are clearly only in the script so that they can end the season with a pointless and masturbatory show down in Alexandria that will ALSO make no sense. If anyone liked this episode, I'm not sorry for you, I just wish you would stop telling Walking Dead you love it while it F*%$s you. I'm on my way to finally leaving this abusive relationship, myself.

Based on character appeal and dramatic anticipation, I should give this season a 5 star, but sometimes it gets frustrating as the group dwindles down and the zombies seem to be winning a war of attrition.  I was really "bummed" when Tyree was killed, and it made no sense to kill Beth(?) right after reuniting with her.  That's the dramatic anticipation--there is always something bad waiting to happen to this group of survivors led by Glen and Rick, Mecchone (sic) and Daryl, especially as you become emotionally invested in the characters. The creators of the show know this and use it to their advantage in moving the storyline forward. Since this is not a "and they lived happily ever after" kind of series, it's getting harder to watch because it always feels like some important character's death is "just around the corner"; and the locations that appear to be a Haven (e.g., the Prison and Terminus) and seem to be the safest consistently turn out to be the worst places to settle down.  "Starting over"repeatedly  becomes the Mantra for the series, but each event causes a little more of the survivors' humanity to be lost.  Very troubling.

As a writer myself, I believe that this has a lot of elements that blend well. The scenes of the individuals don't detract from the story, but gives a much deeper understanding the "Human" aspect of the characters that other shows or movies lack. I believe in many ways, that this show is a reflection of the human psyche that may of us endure in our lives. From poverty, to natural disasters, or a series of bad luck that plague us, we can relate to this on many levels. I sense the realism in this, and also sense that no matter where Rick and the group ends up, the idea of a Utopia will not exist for them because of so many problems with other people. A part of them is still not trusting fully, and even if Alexandria does work out, that knowledge of the past will always be a part of them. Like post tramautic Stress disorder, it takes time and therapy, and this group has it in the spades. Great show, hope to see healing on many levels!

As with most of the Walking Dead episodes, the writers create harrowing situations--over and over again--by having the characters make stupid decisions or by using man-of-few-words miscommunications whereby crucial information is not shared between people who supposedly care about each other. Time and time again, characters split up, walk off without telling anyone where they're going. How many times has one member of the group searched a room *alone*? They get distracted, ponder the meaningless of existence, and then (wow, didn't see that coming) a walker sneaks up on them from behind.

How is it that mindless walkers can travel silently in a woods filled with dead twigs and leaves? But when it comes to bad guys, the walkers almost always make some sound allowing the bad guy to dispatch the walker.

This is just indicative of laziness on the part of the writers. If this show was billed like a campy TV show, similar to the way the old Batman TV show was campy, then it would work. But The Walking Dead takes itself seriously.

More than halfway through Season 5, this is still one of the most compelling character dramas on cable television. The violence and gore may turn off some people, and the inconsistent pacing of the plot may turn off others, but these complaints are generally minor and in my opinion can't outweigh the quality writing, acting, special effects and cinematography. Everyone has their favorite characters and favorite moments. Skeptics can wonder how a show about zombies can be so popular. The answer is: it's not about zombies. It's about people in the most dire circumstances, doing whatever it takes not only to survive, but to truly live, and the show as always does a great job of making that philosophical distinction, constantly digging into the deep and often uncomfortable underpinnings of human nature to craft an evocative drama that will scare you, maybe horrify you, but most of all make you think.

I'm very quickly losing interest in the WD.  I stopped watching after Coda (the end of the hospital) because it's not a series I look forward to anymore.  I'm writing this review with the hope that maybe some of the writers will see this review, or another like it, and take these criticisms to heart for season 6.  Okay, that's not likely to happen.  I mainly just want to vent at how sucky the show has become while I'm waiting for my ambien to kick in :)

spoilers.. and things I wish they did differently... major spoilers

The cannibals were really cool and I like how they had no illusions about themselves-- "yeah sure we're bad guys.  But we gotta eat."  And saying that pretty people taste better.. I'm sure they're right!  There was so much material there, but they just quickly tied it up and jumped to the prison.  I mean farm.  No wait, this year it was a hospital.

But here's my biggest problem with the series-- it's becoming far too predictable.  spoilers... In the first episode, the black guy was a decent human being who hadn't yet lost all hope.. So there was NO DOUBT in my mind that he'd be killed off in a gruesome fashion.  There should be SOME DOUBT for the series to be interesting, right?!  Don't get me wrong, I liked the scene where they were eating his leg, but the pattern of killing nice people is far too obvious.  It's expected, and boring.

Then there's Beth.  Poor sheepish, mousy, rape-bait Beth.  Did anyone think for a second she'd make it out of there alive?  I sure didn't.  That obvious pattern off killing everyone who isn't totally jaded or killing people the second their guard drops is getting annoying.  I guess you're only supposed to become invested in characters who no longer care if they live or die.  Or the 4 main cast members.  I honestly had a doomsday tracker in my brain for Beth, and I  was actually shocked when it looked for second like I might have been wrong.  I also had another doomsday tracker for the big black guy who lost his nerve.  Just wait, once he becomes a bigger part of the story, he's also a goner!  I think the four main cast members are safe, which is why always killing off the likeable people just  comes off as gimmicky to me, and without any real bite.  It's like politicians who throw a lackey under a bus.  It's cheap and just makes me resentful of the series.

And then there's Eugene.  more spoilers.  Honestly, how many people out there thought he was a fake?  I suspect quite a few; I know I did.  It was his mannerisms and 'explanations', sure.  But mainly every time.. let me repeat.. EVERY TIME there's a shred of hope, it gets extinguished.  I get that this is a bleak series.  But constantly dangling hope in front of the audience and then yanking it away (both in terms of plots and killing likeable characters) makes the series repetetive.  For the last few seasons, far too many things were predictable.  And now I'm seeing Rick Grimes as one dimensional.  His last name is 'grimes' because he's always covered in grime.  Wash off your face once in a while!  The series has become obvious with too many closeups, forced moods, predictable deaths, predictable appearances of zombies, with each season only differing by locale.

And where do all the zombies come from?  They remind me of lightning or thunder to help set the mood for a powerful scene.  Sure, people die and get turned into walkers, but it's never just one zombie.  There's always a handful, and they're always just inside the treeline.  You'd think ten years into the zombie  apocalypse there would be stretches of real estate free from walkers.  One year into the apocalypse sure.. you pull off the road, scrape the guts off your windshield, and five walkers emerge.  Now.. I know they gotta follow the graphic novel, but I'd have zombies either evolve a bit, or else get even crazier after eating on other zombies.  I honestly prefer Z- Nation to Walking Dead.  In that series, if someone tries to lighten the mood by telling a damn joke, the writers don't instantly kill them off just to force that constant somber mood.

Look Mr. Walking Dead writer guys.. You're losing audience members.  Okay, that's not true, you're gaining a bigger audience each year.  But just because a show becomes more and more popular doesn't make it more better.

The show is collapsing fast.  The show has always veered roo far away from reality.  Why don't these people ever butcher a cow and enjoy beef?  Or chickens?

Are we supposed to believe the dead killed every living creature except the characters and other twisted people? Why is there no lovable and heroic dog?  Why don't the characters go fishing? Why don't the characters have carefully crafted proceedures for survival instead of a rough shod strategy?  Why haven't the characters obtained good RV's to travel about the land in style while attempting to master their new world.  Mad Max was a survivor.

Instead of focusing on the characters excercising new and interesting survival strategies, with interesting dialogue we get stale flat dialogue, and now the infection of political correctness with a couple of gay characters.  I don't think Im going to waste time or money on this rapidly declining bilge.

I didn't want to watch this show -- just another zombie movie like the ones from the past.  But my son told me it was good and was much more than a gory zombie show.  He was RIGHT!  The interaction among humans trying to survive in a catastrophic world, the assertion of good and evil, the human strength to withstand extreme hardship, are things well represented in the show. There are integrity vs. disloyalty, trust vs. deception, wisdom vs.  naivety and malevolence vs. good It's addicting, like the old "serials" at the movies.  (Only we older guys will remember those).  The acting in The Walking Dead is very good.  It gets gory at times, but that's just part of it... I'm a big fan and thank my son for getting me interested in it.

I wrote this review to help folks who are experiencing sound issues. I had the same issues when trying to play episode 11 with Silverlight. If you are watching on a PC (not sure about Mac or other devices), you can go to "settings" in the top right section of the screen, scroll down, and click on the option to watch the show with Adobe Flash instead of Microsoft Silverlight, then reload the video and watch it. The streaming quality didn't seem to be as good as when played with Silverlight, but the sound works with Flash.

Other than that, I would say that the Walking Dead is more of an "experience" rather than a "TV Show." It provides great fodder for thought and conversation, for appropriate audiences. Enjoy!

I too had no sound for Ep11 and about lost it; even rebooted my computer. Was NOT willing to wait so contacted Customer Service--problem on PC & Mac is Microsoft Silverlight (MS causing a prob?! Go figure!! lol) Need to go into your Video Library and then Settings; change it from using 'recommended' MS Silverlight to Adobe Flash and POOF! *Sound works like magic*!! SO relieved since I stay up late to watch this soon as they're released each week :) NOW, after getting to watch it, waiting for the beginning of NEXT weeks episode is gonna 'slay' me; quite a cliffhanger! lol. **Unfortunately I don't know what will help those on Android devices since Adobe, for their inscrutable ridiculous reasons, stopped supporting Flash for Android! If you're trying to watch on an Android device and have access to a PC or Mac, try that and change these settings instead if you want to watch ASAP (I know I always do!) Hope this helps some of my fellow frustrated fans! :) **EDIT-- More detailed instructions in case the original ones weren't specific enough and and perhaps why a few people voted this Unhelpful:
Hover over "Your Account" >>Select/click on "Your Video Library" in drop down list >>Find and click on "Settings" (on upper right menu bar just below the larger bar with Your Account, Cart etc. It may ask you to log in at this juncture.) >>On "Settings" page scroll down to "Player Preferences"; that's where you'll find the place to switch to Adobe Flash Player to get sound.
